<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Japan to Reform Distribution System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, Friday urged Japan to
undertake fundamental reforms in its distribution system in order
to reduce the high cost of doing business in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body made the appeal Friday in Brussels, with
the publication of the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruling in
Kodak-Fuji case expected in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese distribution system needs to be reformed urgently
in order to reduce the high cost of doing business in the Japanese
market, to improve market access for foreign exporters and service
providers, and to provide more consumer choice," said Sir Leon
Brittan, the European trade commissioner.
</P>
<P>
In the Kodak-Fuji case, the U.S. government took Japan to the
WTO Disputes Settlement Body over restrictions in access for
foreign companies to the Japanese photographic film and paper
market. The commission joined the panel as third party due to its
economic interest in the market.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon said the EU executive body had presented many
proposals to Japan, expecting to see concrete improvements both
through deregulation and rigorous enforcement of competition rules.
</P>
<P>
During the course of the Kodak-Fuji case, Sir Leon said, Japan
said that it had a policy of ensuring non-discriminatory access to
the Japanese distribution system and improving market access in the
photographic film sectors and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to track closely the implementation of this policy
and we welcome the fact that the U.S. and other WTO members intend
to do likewise," he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has recently sent a total of 200
deregulation proposals to the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The commission also noted that the implementation of Japan's
new three-year deregulation program from April 1998 provides an
opportunity for measures to be taken to facilitate access to the
Japanese distribution system for foreign companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
