<HEADLINE> Britain to Send More Fighter Planes to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson announced here today that Britain would send eight
Tornado aircraft to the Gulf region within the next few days to
beef up British military presence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said in a written answer to the British parliament
that the government made the decision following a review of
Britain's military presence in the Gulf "in view of the continuing
refusal of the Iraqi regime to comply fully with the requirements
of the United Nations Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"I have concluded that, as a further precautionary measure, we
should deploy eight Tornado GR1 aircraft, with support, to
Kuwait," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
A BBC television report said that the eight Tornados are
currently based at Brueggen airbase on the Dutch-German border.
</P>
<P>
"With the agreement of the government of Kuwait, appropriate
planning in hand, the Tornados will deploy in the next few days,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the latest eruption of the U.N.-Iraq crisis, Britain has
already sent one of its aircraft carriers and six "sea Harrier"
planes to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
