<HEADLINE> Canada's Unemployment Rate Rises to 8.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment rate rose
0.3 percentage points to 8.9 percent in January, Statistics Canada
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics agency said that the country's employment was
unchanged in January, following strong growth of 366,000 over the
previous 10 months.
</P>
<P>
But unemployment grew by an estimated 54,000, due both to a
rise in temporary layoffs in areas affected by the ice storm and
an increase in the number of people entering the labor market.
</P>
<P>
The majority of job losses happened around the city of
Montreal, where the weather's wrath was most severe.
</P>
<P>
In Ontario province where the storm was limited to its eastern
part, employment grew strongly, rising by 39,000 jobs in the
month.
</P>
<P>
The province of Alberta gained 22,000 jobs and retained the
fastest pace of job growth in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
