<HEADLINE> Nordingham's Houghton Takes over Chinese National Squad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, Feburary 6 (Xinhua) -- Nordingham Forest's assistant
coach Bob Houghton has been picked up as the head coach of the
Chinese national team, the Chinese Football Association (CFA)
announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The position has been vacant after former coach Qi Wusheng
resigned following China's heart-broken defeat in the World Cup
qualifying round last November.
</P>
<P>
Houghton, 51, who arrived here from England on Thursday, will
meet the newly-built national squad in Shanghai on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Houghton, whose contract signed only to the end of the year,
said his goal was to bring together all the Chinese top players
and take a concrete step toward the 2002 World Cup
Finals. Although the news had leaked a few days before, CFA
only comfirmed it today.
</P>
<P>
CFA didn't reveal how much salary Houghton would get.
</P>
<P>
It was said that CFA had targeted a half dozen famous
foreign coachs but finally nailed Houghton.
</P>
<P>
Houghton is not the first foreign coach for the Chinese
national team. Klaus Schlappner, a well-known german coach, was
invited to take charge the squad in 1992, but he lost the position
after failing to steer the team to the World Cup Finals in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The team will fly to Haigeng camp in Yunnan province
for a 20-day training in preparation for the four-team Dynasity
Cup Tournament, starting early March in Japan with South Korea,
Japan and Hong Kong attending.
</P>
<P>
Houghton, whose Nordingham Forest now top the England's
Division A League, had stayed with the Chinese side for a
short period last year as an advisor and a lecturer.
</P>
<P>
The Briton watched China's several matches in the build-up
for the qualifier of World Cup finals. "As a foreign coach, He has
a better understanding about the Chinese team," said Zhang Jilong,
vice president of CFA.
</P>
<P>
"The final decision to choose Houghton as the head coach was
settled after CFA carefully denied several possible foreign
and local candidates," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Houghton believed that it would take a long way for the Chinese
team to qualify for the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
The Briton also said that through the close cooperation and
hard efforts between him and CFA officials, the Chinese squad is
likely to achieve good results under his guide.
</P>
<P>
Houghton has been a coach in the first division clubs in the
United States, Sweden, Saudi Arabia, England and Greece from early
1970s. He guided the Malmo of Sweden to a four-time league
champion and final of European Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
But Houghton is expected to face heavy pressure from nearly one
hundred million Chinese soccer fans. The world's most populous
country, who has built up the world largest soccer market after
introducing a professional league in 1994, has seen all its
previous five bids for the World Cup finals ending in disastrous
failures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
