<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Jobless Rate Near 24-Year Low in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Strong job growth,
particularly in construction and real estate, helped hold the U.S.
unemployment rate at 4.7 percent in January which is near a
24-year low, the Labor Department reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted unemployment rate, the same as
December, was just a bit over November's 4.6 percent rate, lowest
since 1973, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. employers added 358,000 jobs to their payrolls last
month. Construction accounted for 92,000 new jobs, the largest
monthly gain in the category in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
Today's report shows that Asia's financial problems haven't yet
dampened the strongest American labor market in a generation,
despite of the fact that factories report weaker orders in
December and January.
</P>
<P>
In January, only 9,000 of the new jobs came in government, the
rest in private industry.
</P>
<P>
Real estate services had an unusually strong month, adding
10,000 jobs. Computer and data processing services and engineering
and management services continued their rapid growth. However,
health services grew more slowly than usual.
</P>
<P>
Department stores added 31,000 jobs. But miscellaneous retail
establishments, such as book stores, toy stores and catalog sales
operations, had larger-than-usual layoffs following robust holiday
hiring.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing added 43,000 jobs in January, in line with the
growth of the previous three months, with strength in fabricated
metal products, industrial machinery, electronic components and
aircraft. There were job losses in apparel, textiles and leather
products.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the department added statistics on
unemployment by educational level for workers 25 years and older.
Joblessness was 7.2 percent among those without a high school
diploma, 3.9 percent for high school graduates with no college,
3.2 percent for people with post-high school education but without
a bachelor's degree and 1.9 percent for college graduates.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of strength in January, average hourly wages
rose 4 cents to 12.51 dollars. Over the past year, they're up 46
cents, or 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The average workweek increased from 34.6 hours to 34.8 hours,
seasonally adjusted. But the manufacturing workweek edged from
42.2 hours to 42.1 hours. Factory overtime held at 4.9 hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
