<HEADLINE> Jail Sentence for Turkish Hijackers of Maltese Airliner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 6 (xinhua) -- A court in Cologne Friday
sentenced two Turkish men to imprisonment for hijacking an Air
Malta Boeing 737 to Germany last June.
</P>
<P>
Nusret Akmercan received a term of five years and nine months
in prison while his "assistant," Ismail Beyazpinar, to four years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
The two accused, both at the age of 25, hijacked the Maltese
airliner bound for Turkey on June 9, 1997 by using a dummy bomb.
Aboard the plane were 78 passengers and six crewmen.
</P>
<P>
They surrendered later to police at the Cologne-Bonn airport.
</P>
<P>
The two Turkish men said that by the hijacking, they wanted to
draw attention to the situation of Mehmet Ali Agca, a Turkish
national who is in jail in Italy for attempted assassination of
Pope John Paul II in May 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
