<HEADLINE> Mugabe Blames Media for Distorting Land Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Friday told the international community that his
government had no evil intentions in trying to resolve land
imbalances, but had become a victim of biased media coverage.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon he hosted for diplomatic corps and
representatives of international organizations based in Zimbabwe,
Mugabe said the donor community had been misled by distorted
press reports.
</P>
<P>
"We want to assure the donor community that our intentions are
not evil ones as some donors might have been led to believe by
the barrage of largely distorted, biased, negative, mischievous
and unconstructive press reports concerning the government's
intentions on the land question," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact was that his government was trying to resolve
the situation of imbalance in a peaceful and orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe last year announced a list of over 1,400 farms which
have been targeted for designation, but the government has
promised that it will only compensate for improvements made and
not for the land itself.
</P>
<P>
The move was met with criticism from the major donor of the
resettlement program, Britain, which has said it would only offer
financial support if the program was meant to resolve the needs
of the poor.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Commercial Farmers Union of Zimbabwe, who own
most of the targeted land, have disagreed with the way the
government is going about land acquisition and have offered its
own land plan, saying enough land could be obtained on a willing
seller-willing buyer basis.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also sought to reassure the international community
that the violent demonstrations which rocked the country in
recent months were not a reflection of the wishes of the masses
of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"I want to assure you that those violent and riotous
demonstrations have been condemned by the majority of the
peace-loving people of Zimbabwe who do not wish to see their
recurrence," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
