<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office Minister
Derek Fatchett will visit Oman, the United Arab Emirates and Egypt
next week to discuss with leaders of the three countries the
current U.N.-Iraq crisis and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office statement issued this afternoon said that the
target of the mission on 10-13 February was to brief Britain's
Gulf allies "on the UK's efforts to achieve a diplomatic solution
to the crisis."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett was quoted as saying, "Britain has strong historical
ties with the countries of the Gulf. We were resolute in standing
by our regional allies when Kuwait was invaded in 1991."
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein is threatening Gulf security again by refusing
to let the U.N.'s weapons inspectors do their job," Fathchett
said. "In the face of this renewed threat, our commitment to
enforcing the international community's will is unwavering."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett stressed that cooperation with Britain's Gulf partners
"will play an essential part in bringing about the diplomatic
solution we all want."
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Iraqi situation, Fatchett will discuss with his
Egyptian hosts the Middle East peace process, other regional
issues and bilateral cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N.-Iraq standoff continued deteriorating as
the British government announced this afternoon that it would send
eight Tornado fighter planes to Kuwait in an effort to beef up
British military presence in the Gulf. 
</P>
