<HEADLINE> France Welcomes UN Extension of MISAB Mission in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- France Friday welcomed the
extension by the United Nations Security Council of the mandate
for the Inter-African Mission of Supervision of Bangui Accords
(MISAB) in the Central African Republic until March 16.
</P>
<P>
"This vote is the first step toward the definition of the next
peacekeeping operation (in the Central African Republic)," said
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The MISAB, manned by soldiers from Senegal, Chad, Gabon, Mali,
Burkina Faso and Togo, has been deployed since January 1997 in the
Central African Republic with logistic and financial support from
France.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council will vote on March 16 the
dispatch of a 1,400-man U.N. peacekeeping force to the Central
African Republic to replace the MISAB.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force will be in charge of security and supervise
elections later this year in the Central African Republic, which
was plunged into turmoil by several army mutinies in 1996.
</P>
<P>
France will also withdraw its 1,400 troops from the country as
part of re-deployment of French troops on the African continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
