<HEADLINE> UN Appeals for 10 Mln Dlrs for Repatriation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
refugee agency today appealed for more than 10 million U.S.
dollars for the repatriation of refugees of Mali and Niger who are
in Mauritania, Burkina Faso and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said
the sum would cover activities during 1998.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 have returned to Mali since 1995. Over 90,000
of them received assistance from UNHCR. At least 11,000 of the
remaining refugees are expected to be repatriated in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations refugee agency said it was supporting
reconciliation meetings between refugees and other communities in
Mali. UNHCR is also encouraging the country' authorities to visit
camps in order to build confidence among former exiles about the
possibility of returning home.
</P>
<P>
According to UNHCR, the integration process in Mali is fragile
and depends heavily on the development of the arid north of the
country. the agency said it was digging and remarking 135 water
outlets of all types in that region.
</P>
<P>
In Niger, the refugee agency was planning to complete its
repatriation operation during 1998 if security concerns,
particularly criminality, did not multiply.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 4,000 refugee who fled political turmoil and
armed rebellion in the late 1980s and renewed insurgency in the
early 1990s are set to return from Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
