<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book on Refugees Launched in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- "The State of the World's
Refugees 1997-98", published by the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), was formally launched here
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to launch the new book, David
Lambo, UNHCR regional liaison representative, said the African
continent may have the largest number of refugees in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and most of
member states have made resolutions and activities to the problem
of refugees in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Lambo said, the UNHCR's new book takes a detailed look at the
problem of forced displacement, focusing on those groups who are
of primary concern to the organization: refugees, asylum seekers,
the internally displaced, returnee and stateless people, adding
that the book also provides a detailed agenda for action,
suggesting ways in which the protection of people might be
reinforced.
</P>
<P>
Drawing upon case studies from every part of the world, the
book suggests that humanitarian action can play an important role
in defending the rights of people who have been uprooted or
threatened with displacement. Referring to this, he stressed that
such action can never act as a substitute for the protection
which states must provide for their own citizens.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of OAU commission of twenty on refugees, Ismail
Chergui, Algerian Ambassador to Ethiopia and First Vice-Chairman
of OAU Commission of Twenty on refugees, introduced OAU's
resolutions and activities on protection and resolution of
African refugees and displaced people during the last few years
at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the book launched here today, some 22.72 million
people around the world belong to people of concern to the UNHCR.
Among them, 13.2 million are refugees, 4.85 million internally
displaced people, 3.31 million returnee and 1.36 million people
are others of concern.
</P>
<P>
In sub-Saharan Africa, 7.84 million people are people of
concern to the UNHCR. Among them, 4.34 million are African
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at the press conference, Lambo said,
Ethiopia, at the center of the Horn of Africa, provides asylum to
refugees from Somalia, Sudan, Djibouti, Kenya and various other
countries with the total refugees population of some 321,100 at
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an estimated 24,000 Ethiopian refugees are waiting
to return home, including some 22,000 Ethiopians living in Sudan,
1,200 in Kenya and the rest in Yemen and other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
