<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Evident Link Between Breast Implant, Disease: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Silicone breast implants are
unlikely to damage the immune system and cause disease, according
to a new study published today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers wrote in the British Medical Journal that little
likelihood of association has been found between breast implants
and connective tissue disease.
</P>
<P>
Proportion of the hospitalized among women with implants was
not significantly higher than is found among those who have not
had implants, they said.
</P>
<P>
The research was carried out in Sweden among over 7,000 women
with breast implants and a control group of over 3,000 women who
had undergone reduction surgeries.
</P>
<P>
The authors, from the Karolinska Institute in Stockholm, found
that of the women with implants, 29 were hospitalized for
connective tissue disease as compared to a national average of
25.5.
</P>
<P>
And of the women who had undergone reduction, 14 needed
hospital treatment as opposed to the expected 10.5.
</P>
<P>
After a direct comparison of the two groups, the researchers
found that those with implants had a slightly lower risk of
connective tissue disease than those who had undergone breast
reduction
</P>
<P>
"Our data add to the emerging consensus that there is no
important association between breast implants and connective
tissue disease." they concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
