<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalia's Baidoa Still Under Control of H. Aidid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 6 (Xinhua) -- As the time set for the
withdrawal of Hussein Aidid's forces from the town of Baidoa has
expired Thursday, there are no visible signs yet for the pull
back of those forces from the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cairo peace declaration, Hussein Aidid's
forces should have pulled back from the Rahanwein dominated
regions of Bay and Bakol 10 days before the convening of the
National Reconciliation Conference scheduled to begin on February
15.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Hussein Aidid's top aids, there are
extensive meetings currently undergoing between Hussein Aidid and
high level politicians from the Rahanwein communities in charge
of the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) here in Mogadishu for the
mechanisms in which the force encampment would smoothly work out.
</P>
<P>
The top aids also said, according to the Cairo agreement,
combatant forces from both sides should be demobilized and
neutral forces should be deployed there to safeguard the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hussein Aidid is also meeting his force commanders
for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
The official who declined to reveal his name said he is not
sure whether the Reconciliation Conference will start according
to the time table; "so the dead line for the withdrawal will
still remain 10 days before the conference is to begin in
Baidoa," he said, added: "we're ready to abide by the agreement."
</P>
<P>
According to confidential reports, the financial package for
convening the conference in Baidoa is yet to arrive.
</P>
<P>
Since their arrival late last month, Hussein Aidid and his
counterpart politicians have been busy working on pacifying the
capital where tangible progress has been made after successive
peace rallies have been held across the green lines and in
Mogadishu's main soccer stadium. They were followed by a tour by
the former rival factions with hundreds of battle wagons of the
main streets of the capital including Bermuda neighborhood where
the heaviest armed confrontation occurred in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
Streams of people can now be seen walking in the streets of
Bermuda and across the former green lines as some people are also
repairing their houses so as to revitalize the life back to
normal after six years.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Mogadishu citizens are still looking forward to
seeing the port and airport being opened in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Late General Mohamed Aidid has invaded the regions of Bay and
Bakol in late 1995 to destroy a local autonomous authority
established by the U.N. Operation in Somalia (UNOSOM) in the
region, something he has seen as a threat to his dream
administration.
</P>
<P>
The town of Baidoa, 245 km Southwest of Mogadishu, has since
then experienced a series of armed confrontations. However, since
the Cairo meeting those regions have been calm as their political
leaders have themselves been among the signatories of the Cairo
peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
