<HEADLINE> Britain Calls For IMF Code On Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain has called on the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to introduce a fiscal
transparency code to prevent sudden outbreak of financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that reform of the IMF, including the
allocation of new funds, will be the top agenda at the G-7 finance
ministers meeting here later this month.
</P>
<P>
The Times today quoted British Chancellor Gordon Brown as
saying, "Firms and markets need clear signals from governments
about policy if they are to make the right decisions and feel
confident about the future."
</P>
<P>
Brown, who spoke at a meeting of European and Asian finance
deputies (ASEM) Thursday, also gave a strong warning against
retreating into protectionism in an attempt to resolve the
problems.
</P>
<P>
The ASEM meeting concluded with a call for the IMF to improve
its surveillance techniques and for the establishment of a
regional surveillance organization for Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, Sir Nigel Wicks, who chaired the meeting, said he
believed the impact of the Asian financial crisis would be
manageable for the world economy and "relatively modest" in
Europe. 
