<HEADLINE> London, Paris Stocks Hit New Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all surged and ended the week higher Friday, with London and Paris
storming to new record closing highs, propelled by US economic
data which raised hopes of no further interest rate rise anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market made the record books again
after a morning of sluggish falls, with the FTSE 100 index closing
23.3 points up at a new record high of 5,629.7.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector, which had been one of the main powerhouses
driving the stock market up, staged a dramatic comeback after this
morning's fall.
</P>
<P>
The market was also supported by news that the US economy is in
good growth and under weak inflationary pressures and by another
solid performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris also ended the week 27.06 points
firmer at 3,216.66, an all-time peak for the second session in a
row.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that shares prices edged into positive territory
following stronger-than-expected US jobs data.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, at floor trading, which closes before Wall Street
opens, the DAX-30 share index ended down 52.13 at 4,496.33 as the
market consolidated from Thursday's record gains ahead of the
release of US jobs data later.
</P>
<P>
However, in later electronic trading, the IBIS DAX index closed
42.19 points higher at 4,536.91. 
</P>
