<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Jolts Afghanistan, 3,200 Killed:Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 6 (Xinhua) -- A strong earthquake jolted
northern Afghanistan this week, leaving at least 3,200 people dead
and thousands of others homeless, the Taliban's ambassador to
Pakistan and embassy officials confirmed here late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Maulawi Dilawar told Xinhua by telephone that the quake, which
measured 6.1 on the Richter Scale, hit the country's northern
Takhor province Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Afghan sources here said news of the quake in the remote
northern province was sketchy and it did not reach the Afghan
capital of Kabul until Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dilawar said the epicenter of the quake was near Rustaq, about
20 km northwest of Talogan, provincial capital of Takhor, which is
controlled by anti-Taliban warlord and former Afghanistan's
military chief Ahmad Masood.
</P>
<P>
He said official figures put the latest death toll at 3,200 and
about 2,000 others were injured.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Yusef, an official of the Taliban government's embassy
here, said earlier that as many as 4,000 people were killed in the
quake and 15,000 left homeless.
</P>
<P>
Dilawar said Taliban authorities had expressed its readiness to
provide unconditional assistance to the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Omar, the supreme leader of the hardline Taliban
militia, has also expressed deep grief over the disaster and
appealed to the international community for immediate aid.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Friday night said six villages in Chaiaab
district were completely demolished in the quake and about 3,000
bodies had already been recovered from the debris.  
</P>
