<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Killings in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
condemned Friday recent killings in the British province of
Northern Ireland and urged groups to focus on talks instead.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair at the White House, Clinton said the United
States would continue to do all it could to advance the cause of
peace, and asked Blair how best the U.S. could help.
</P>
<P>
"I unequivocally condemn recent sectarian killings and beatings
and threats" in Northern Ireland, Clinton said. "Nothing worth
having can be accomplished through violence."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also commended Blair for the "courageous steps" he is
taking "in cooperation with the Irish government to promote a
climate of confidence and hope in Northern Ireland."
</P>
<P>
He said multi-party peace negotiations, which resume Monday in
Belfast, "provide the best chance for a real solution to that
conflict. I urge all the parties to show the vision and
forbearance and the determination to succeed."
</P>
<P>
In response, Blair said he appreciated the willingness shown by
Clinton and members of Congress he met Thursday to advance the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It isn't going to be easy, these things never are," Blair
said. "But we do believe that we have the best chance that we have
had for many generations to secure peace. And I wanted to
emphasize to you our total and complete determination and
commitment to find a peaceful way through."
</P>
<P>
"What we must ensure is that those random, brutal, unjustified
actions of violence, perpetrated by a small majority, must not
frustrate the wish of the overwhelming majority of people in
Northern Ireland to secure a peaceful and stable future for
themselves," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister arrived here Thursday for his first
official visit to the United States since he took office. 
</P>
