<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan-IMF Talks on Loans May Reopen Later This </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) may reopen negotiations with Kenya on aid loans in the
second half of this year, Reimer Carstens, the IMF resident
representative, told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of talks over a three-year 205 million U.S.
Dollar aid loans halted mid last year, is widely believed to be
key for re-building up confidence of foreign investors to Kenya
now suffering from poor infrastructure, El Nino rains and tribal
violence.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very optimistic (about the talks being resumed)," said
Carstens in an exclusive interview with Xinhua ahead of Sunday's
arrival of a six-member IMF team led by Goodall Gondwe, deputy
director of the IMF's African Department.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi "is most likely to meet the
chief of the team," said Carstens.
</P>
<P>
The team will stay here for two weeks to review current
economic reforms and "determine measures that could be taken to
maintain macro-economic stability," especially in the budget
term, according to a governmental statement issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall in the budget of the 1997/98 fiscal year ending
on June 30 this year, partly caused by the government's
compromise to raise teachers's wages of up to 200 percent, will
be seriously discussed by the two sides, said Carstens.
</P>
<P>
He said the team will not fix the date for the negotiations
but will expectedly lay the basis for initiating talks once it is
satisfied with implementation of the actions which Kenya agreed
to take during the last IMF visit in August and September.
</P>
<P>
At that time, The Kenyan government pledged to "strengthen
management of the energy sector, safeguard the independence of
the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA), ensure that Anti-Corruption
Authority would be independent and establish accountability for
past financial infractions."
</P>
<P>
IMF is satisfied with the progress so far Kenya has made in
these fields, said Carstens, citing the improvement in energy
sector, the creation of an anti-graft authority and the
staffdowning of KRA.
</P>
<P>
However, such progresses are not enough to meet the IMF
demands, he stressed, adding that ensuring the accountability and
transparency in the management of public finances is "the most
outstanding issue."
</P>
<P>
He also complained that the Kenyan government moves "very
slow" in dealing with exposed corruption cases, especially in the
famous Goldenburg scandal.
</P>
<P>
The IMF signed with Kenya the three-year loan package under
the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) in April 1995
and stopped the disbursement of the first year's 37 million
Dollar slice on July 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hopes now hinge on salvaging the remaining 148 million Dollars
and accompanying structural adjustment credits from the World
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Briefs Annan on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of ECOWAS Committee of
Five on Sierra Leone Friday briefed UN Secretary-general Kofi
Annan on the situation in the crisis-ridden west African country
before a briefing to the UN Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The committee, led by Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi,
also sought the support of the UN to ensure that the peace plan
for Sierra Leone was implemented within the stipulated time, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) set up
the committee in the wake of last May 25 coup that toppled the
legitimate government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made of Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea
and Liberia, signed a peace plan with the ruling military junta
last October in Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the junta is to quit office by April 22 this
year.
</P>
<P>
However, Ikimi told the secretary-general that the junta in
Sierra Leone had refused to implement the peace plan by setting
conditions which included re-composition of the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG and the release of their
deputy leader Foday Sankoh from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the junta has indicated that the April 22
deadline will not be possible, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that ECOWAS was not ready to yield to the junta's
demand and would want the Security Council and the international
community to send a clear message that the deadline is still
valid.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, ECOMOG has not been able to deploy its
troops because of the intransigence of the junta. The lack of UN
military observer mission to support the efforts of ECOWAS has
also placed the sub-region in a "dilemma".
</P>
<P>
The committee briefed the UN on the situation in Sierra Leone
last November.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Ikimi noted, the situation there has gotten worse
as the junta created conditions to impede the implementation of
the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Annan pledged the UN's assistance at
implementing the peace agreement and promised to make a
recommendation to the Security Council for a military observer
team for Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fighting has resumed between ECOMOG and junta
forces in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged heavy shellings. No casualty figures
have been available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
