<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Blair Threaten Iraq With Tough Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and British Prime Minister both warned Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein Friday that they were prepared to take tough action if he
did not comply with U.N. resolutions over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference, Clinton said the United States and
Britain "stand together" with a determination to "prevent him
(Saddam) from threatening his neighbors and the world with weapons
of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
"Let me be clear, if Saddam Hussein does not comply with the
unanimous will of the international community, we must be prepared
to act," he said.
</P>
<P>
And Blair echoed Clinton with the remarks that "we must
prepare."
</P>
<P>
Blair said he and Clinton discussed a range of different
topics. "At the top of the list, of course, was the situation in
respect of Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"What we agreed was that we had to do three things in
particular," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair outlined the three things as the first to "educate" the
public opinion to get known the importance of weapons inspections;
the second to solve the Iraqi crisis through diplomacy, which he
said should be "based on, and fully consistent with, the
principles that we have set out;" and the third to prepare for
military action "in case diplomacy cannot work."
</P>
<P>
Britain is the only country that stands firm with the United
States. Other European countries and Middle East states show no
enthusiasm for military action and the three other permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council, Russia, France and China,
are opposed to any military action.
</P>
<P>
While Clinton said there was more international support for the
tough U.S. and British line than it may appear, U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen expressed disappointment with the response
of other U.N. Security Council members on the U.S. line as he
started his Europe and Gulf trip to rally support for possible
military action.
</P>
<P>
"I have been disappointed with the Security Council's action to
date that they have passed resolutions and yet seem unwilling to
condemn Saddam's action or say that he has been in either
significant or material breach," Cohen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
