<HEADLINE> Clinton Vows Investigation of Cable Car Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
vowed on Friday that a fatal cablecar disaster in Italy caused by
a low-flying U.S. warplane, would be fully investigated.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference with visiting British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, Clinton said that he called Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi and told him that he felt "heartsick" about
the disaster.
</P>
<P>
"I would make absolutely sure there was a no holds barred, full
investigation on what happened; that the Italians would be kept
fully informed and be a part of it," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said military flights such as the one involved in the
disaster were "inherently dangerous" but pledged, "I will do
everything I can to find out what happened and take appropriate
action and to satisfy the people of Italy that we have done the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Friday, the U.S. military acknowledged that the
EA-6B warplane that caused the disaster in which 20 people were
killed was flying far too low. It should have been no lower than
304 meters above the ground.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was based at Aviano, Italy, part of the
NATO-led effort to patrol Bosnia, slashed through the cables of a
ski lift car at the resort of Cavalese in northern Italy, sending
the victims hurtling to their deaths on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The victims included a 13-year-old boy and tourists from Italy,
Germany, Belgium, Poland, the Netherlands and Austria.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, the U.S. military loses about 200 people
every year in military service in America on training exercise or
otherwise on duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
