<HEADLINE> Iraq Voices Opposition to New UN Oil-for-Food Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Government
categorically rejected the main parts of the new oil-for-food plan
proposed by UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday, according to a
letter from the Iraqi Government which was released here today.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the Security Council of the United Nations,
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-sahaf said Iraq opposed
the UN directives on how goods should be purchased and
distributed.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday recommended to raise the
amount of oil Iraq could sell from 2 billion U.S. dollars to 5.2
billion for the next six months, a move aimed to alleviate
sufferings of the Iraqi people from the effects of UN sanctions
imposed on it since 1990.
</P>
<P>
"If no increase had been approved, no oil will be pumped before
Iraq has prepared a supplementary plan concerning the increase and
the Secretary-General has approved that plan," said the Iraqi
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqi Government has sole responsibility for preparing the
purchase and distribution plan. We categorically reject this
formula and wish to state that any addition to the purchase and
distribution plan remains the sole responsibility of the Iraqi
Government," the foreign minister was responding to the the UN
directive that says how much money is to be spent for certain
categories of foods.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to meet to review the
recommendations by the UN chief next Monday.  
</P>
