<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Efforts Go on to End Iraqi-US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Arab
League (AL) Esmat Abdel-Meguid said here Friday that international
efforts were still going on to help end peacefully the standoff
between Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Russian envoy Victor Posuvalyuk still remained in Baghdad to
look for more progress in his mission, said Abdel-Meguid who just
arrived in Amman from Iraq where he exerted efforts to help end
the crisis of arms inspections between Iraq and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
International efforts, spearheaded by Russia, was expected to
put an end to the standoff as Iraq had already changed its mind
and agreed to open most of the suspected sites for inspection,
he told reporters after a short meeting with Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief said that Jordan also joined international efforts
by promising maximum work for a peaceful solution. He said Majali
told him that Jordan would not allow any country to use its
territory and airspace to kick off any military actions against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan hoped that the crisis would be solved through dialogue
and in the framework of respecting Iraq's sovereignty and
dignity, said Abdel-Meguid who will leave for Cairo soon.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that international efforts were going on, the
situation was still very dangerous, he said, adding that if peace
efforts failed and war prevailed, the region would be ravaged by
instability.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge
of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction from searching
presidential palaces suspected of hiding the banned weapons,
triggering its current standoff with the Untied States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has threatened to take military actions to force Iraq
to grant free access to the UNSCOM if diplomacy fails to exact
Iraq's full compliance with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Iraq, Abdel-Meguid also exchanged views with
France's presidential special envoy Bertrand Dufourcq on possible
solutions to the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
They both agreed on the necessity to attain a compromise
settlement to end the crisis through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Abdel-Meguid, who arrived in Baghdad Wednesday, is
the first ever by an Arab League chief since the end of the 1991
Gulf War which drove Iraq out of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
