<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Americans in Kuwait to Take Precautions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The State Department on
Friday released copies of an announcement by U.S. Embassy in
Kuwait, urging U.S. citizens there to take precautions for
possible military hostilities with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The embassy urged the U.S. citizens there to maintain an
adequate supply of food and water at home, make sure cars are in
good working order, and keep gas tanks full and check oil,
coolant, tires and batteries.
</P>
<P>
It also urged them to assemble all vital documents such as
passports, birth and marriage records, vaccination, insurance and
bank records in one readily accessible location.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said that "these are precautionary measure. We
are not advising Americans to leave."
</P>
<P>
The announcement was issued at a time when the United States
is preparing for a possible military attack on Iraq as it deemed
diplomatic efforts made by the international community has been
almost exhausted. 
