<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Afghan Earthquake May Exceed 4,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from a
devastating earthquake that hit the remote northern Afghan
province of Takhor this week could exceed 4,000, Afghan sources in
Pakistan said late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press, some
3,600 bodies had been recovered from the debris in Takhor province
and the toll is expected to rise as the rescue work is going on.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Taliban's Ambassador to Pakistan, Maulawi Dilawar,
said that at least 3,200 people were killed and 2,000 others
injured. About 15,000 houses were razed by the quake which jolted
the province on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the exact casualties could not be known yet as relief
operations were extremely difficult in the mountainous and
snow-blanketed area, said the Afghan sources in Peshawar, a major
city in northwest Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake measuring 6.1 on the Richter Scale
was near the town of Rustaq, about 20 km northwest of Talogan,
capital of Takhor province. Takhor is now under the control of
anti-Taliban strongman and Afghanistan's former military chief
Ahmad Masood.
</P>
<P>
News of the quake in the remote and mountainous area did not
reach Islamabad until Friday and the details were scant and
difficult to confirm.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Friday night, the subsequent
landslides in the affected area caused much of the destruction.
Thousands of mud and brick homes perched on hillsides were buried
under rubble, and heavy winter snows were also hindering the
rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
United Nations and Red Cross officials here said they were
going to arrange for relief teams to travel to the affected area
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring Tajikistan has already sent relief teams to Rustaq,
only 50 km away from the Tajik border. Iran and Pakistan are also
planning to send rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Taliban's top leader Burhanuddin Rabbani has declared
Saturday a mourning day for the victims of the earthquake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
