<HEADLINE> Clinton Says He Never Consider Resigning Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday said that he would "never" consider resigning over the
alleged sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, Clinton once again refused to give detailed explanation
about the issue. He has repeatedly denied having a sexual
relationship with former white house intern Monica Lewinsky and
encouraging her to lie under oath about it.
</P>
<P>
Asked at what point he might consider resigning, Clinton said
firmly, "Never... I would never walk away from the people of this
country and the trust they've placed in me."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times and the Washington Post reported Friday he
called his personal secretary, Betty Currie, last month to his
office to go over what she remembered about Lewinsky's visits to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers said Clinton led Currie through an account of
his relationship with Lewinsky, who had worked in the White House
in 1995 and 1996 and then returned 37 times after taking a job at
the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers said Clinton's meeting with Currie occurred the
day after Clinton gave a deposition on January 17 in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment lawsuit in which he reportedly denied a
sexual affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, Clinton denied trying to influence
Currie's recollection, saying: "I never told anybody to do
anything but tell the truth."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would not discuss details of the case because
"I'm honoring the rules of the investigation. And if someone else
is leaking unlawfully out of the grand jury proceeding, that's a
different story."
</P>
<P>
"I have tried to bring an end to this sort of thing in our
public life, I've tried to bring the American people together,
I've tried to depersonalize politics and take the venom out of it.
And the harder I've tried to do it, the harder others have pulled
in the other direction," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
