<HEADLINE> France Still Hopeful of Peaceful Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 7 (Xinhua) -- French envoy Betrand
Dufourq said here Saturday that his country is still hopeful
of diplomatic solution to the current Iraq-UN stand-off on
arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement to Kuwait News Agency at Kuwait
Airport before ending his short visit to the country that
his country will "employ every possible effort to reach a
diplomatic and peaceful end of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
"We should continue efforts for a diplomatic solution," he
said, but he added that "France was concerned about ensuring
Iraq's respect of the United Nations resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait was the last leg of Dufourq's regional tour which
also took him to Egypt, Syria and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Dufourq said French President Chirac asked him to "inform
the countries in the region with which we maintain close
relations on the reality of the situation as I saw it in
Baghdad, and especially to inform his Highness the Emir of
Kuwait about the situation."
</P>
<P>
Dufourq went for immediate talks with Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah upon his arrival earlier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that "I noticed during my tour that our concern to
ensure Iraq's respect of the United Nations resolutions is shared
by all the four countries I visited."
</P>
<P>
On whether he was carrying some Iraqi proposals about the
crisis, he said he would refrain from elaborating on the
matter until he first briefs President Chirac on the outcome
of his mission.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said recently "France
will continue to hold talks with all the parties concerned to
avoid the use of force which could have severe consequences for
Iraq and all the countries of the region."
</P>
<P>
The current stand-off led to a U.S. and British military
buildup in the Gulf to prepare for a military strike against
Iraq in case the ongoing international diplomacy to end the
crisis fails.
</P>
<P>
Russia, France and China oppose the use of force against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
France rejected the recent Iraqi proposal to allow limited
and conditional access to the presidential sites, but French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said last week that the Iraqis
has "made a step forward" and needed to "make additional
gestures,"  
</P>
