<HEADLINE> Guangdong Enterprises Benefit From Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 7 (Xinhua) -- State enterprises in south
China's Guangdong Province are improving their performances
through mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen Konka Electronic Group is one example. Early in 1993
the company merged with the Mudanjiang Television Plant in
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province. And in 1995 and 1997 it
bought into Ruyi Electric Appliance Corp. of northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, and a TV factory in east China's Anhui
Province. Konka holds 60 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
The Konka phenomenon aroused attention nationwide. Some other
businesses in the province followed suit, and have been doing just
as well.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the Guangdong Kelon Group merged an engine company in
southwestern Sichuan Province and a refrigerator plant in
northeastern Liaoning Province to develop a refrigerator
production base in the area with an annual capacity of one
million. Meanwhile, Shenzhen Bao'an Group bought into two
Shanghai companies.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen Sanjiu (Triple Nine) Group has purchased 45 otherwise
bankrupt enterprises in 20 provinces and cities, half of which now
are making a profit.
</P>
<P>
Other enterprise groups are also doing well, taking advantage
of their name brands, technology, and high quality to combine with
their partners' factory buildings, equipment and labor force.
</P>
</TEXT>
