<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two UNSCOM Teams leave Iraq After Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 7 (Xinhua)-- Two teams of international
weapons experts of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM on
disarmament in Iraq) left Baghdad Saturday, concluding their
six-day missions in Iraq, the Iraqi news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A missile warheads team, led by a Russian expert Nikita
Simidovic, and a chemical team led by a German expert Horst Rib,
held technical evaluation meetings with Iraqi officials led by
Oil Minister Mohammed Resheed on material and scientific evidence
Iraq had presented to prove its cleanness of mass-destructive
weapons.
</P>
<P>
These meetings, started from February 1, aim at ironing out
differences between Iraq and UNSCOM and evaluate progress made
by Iraq in disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared many times that it has no prohibited weapons
and demanded therefore an end to the economic sanctions imposed
on it for more than seven years now since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to those technical evaluation
meetings, UNSCOM will discuss in Bahrain on how to write a report
it will submit to UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
So far, the conclusion of those meetings is not known.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq can not be lifted unless
UNSCOM verifies that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
A standoff between Iraq and UNSCOM is not over as Iraq is
till opposing free access of the UNSCOM inspectors to some
suspected presidential palaces. Diplomatic efforts by Russia,
France, Turkey and the Arab League failed to ease the tension.
The United States and Britain have threatened to use force to
force Iraq to comply fully with the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
