<HEADLINE> France Reacts to Corsican Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 7 (Xinhua) -- France on Saturday reacted with
consternation to the assassination of Claude Erignac, prefect of
the Mediterranean island of Corsica.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police are searching for two young men who were
seen spraying a rain of bullets on Erignac from a running-by car
in the center of Ajaccio, capital of Corsica, when Erignac was
going to a classical music concert with his wife.
</P>
<P>
Reacting with anger to the murder, President Jacques Chirac
said the rule of the state must be respected in Corsica, which is
known for the violence from nationalist movements claiming
independence from France for the island.
</P>
<P>
But all the French newspapers Saturday remain prudent in
guessing the identity of the murderer, which remains unclaimed up
to now, because this is the first case of assassination of a
senior French government representative within more than 20 years
on the island.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the investigation said the murder does not
look like the work of nationalist militants, such as the Front
National pour Liberation de Corse (FNLC), and could be simply an
act of crime.
</P>
<P>
However, the radical wing of FNLC, FNLC-Canal Historique,
announced the ending of a truce with the government two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Purely criminal motive in the assassination is not ruled out by
investigators, as Corsica remains one of the most economically
underprivileged parts of France.
</P>
<P>
France was hit by a wave of urban violence over the past few
months, in which discontent youths burnt cars and targeted public
properties in riots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
