<HEADLINE> Emergency Circular Calls for Crackdown On Fake Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration of
Industry and Commerce has issued an emergency circular demanding a
severe crackdown on the manufacture and sale of poisoned alcoholic
drinks and other fake products.
</P>
<P>
The document followed recent instructions by State President
Jiang Zemin when he heard about the deaths in north China's Shanxi
Province as a result of local people drinking poisonous alcoholic
beverages.
</P>
<P>
Jiang has asked the concerned departments to strengthen
controls over market activities and to reinforce efforts to police
those engaged in producing and trading phony commodities.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the administration ordered its local
counterparts to launch an overall crackdown on the manufacture and
sales of alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
All those incapable of making quality alcoholic drinks must be
closed down, while those who have broken the law must be referred
to law-enforcement bodies, the document says.
</P>
<P>
The administration ordered a complete investigation of the
Shanxi case and severe punishment for the law violators.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, the Shanxi provincial government held
an emergency teleconference on the issue today. The province plans
to launch a special campaign to deal with the production and sale
of fake alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, 27 people have died and nearly
200 others hospitalized after drinking the lethal methyl alcohol
in the cities of Shuozhou and Taiyuan. Most of those hospitalized
have recovered and have been discharged from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Local administrations for technical supervision have recovered
a large amount of fake alcoholic products in the provinces of
Heilongjiang, Jilin and Hebei as well as Beijing Municipality and
the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
