<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Money Worship, Hedonism Contribute Most to Woman Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Money worship and hedonism are
the most important reasons listed for China's woman crime in a
recent survey conducted jointly by the Beijing Women's Federation
and the Beijing Woman Procurators Association.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 100 female prisoners currently serving sentences
at the Yanqing Prison in suburban Beijing showed that 35 percent
of the crimes committed by women were mostly property-related. The
motive for these crimes was listed as money worship and
pleasure-seeking.
</P>
<P>
Most of these female prisoners had good jobs and relatively
high wages before committing crimes, the survey said, but they
tended to view money as a "universal need" to fulfill their
desires.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, revenge relating to love and family
affairs ranked as the second major cause of crime for women.
</P>
<P>
"If women were abandoned by their lovers or husbands or hurt by
various family disputes, many of them tended to take revenge
without considering the consequences," the survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
The survey said the lack of legal awareness is another
important reason for crimes by women in China, as 60 percent of
the surveyed responded that they "know little about the law."
</P>
<P>
"The lack of legal consciousness prevents many women from using
correct legal methods to protect their interests," an expert
commented.
</P>
<P>
Among the 100 female prisoners surveyed, 42 were jobless before
being jailed, 36 were cadres, 59 were married, and 49 are between
26 and 35 years old.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of this survey was to know more about woman
prisoners' minds to better help them and to prevent other crimes
by women," said one survey organizer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakstan Wins First Hockey Game in Nagano Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Kazakstan defeated Italy 5-3
to win the opening game of the men's ice hockey tournament at the 18th
Olympic Winter Games here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The loser, which finished 9th at the last winter Olympics in
Lillehammer, Norway four years ago, took the first period with 3-1 but
failed to score in the following two periods.
</P>
<P>
In another match of Group A, Austria played to a 2-2 draw against
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
While in Group B, Germany beat Japan 3-1 in a brawl-affected game
and Belarus beat France 4-0.
</P>
<P>
Winners of each group will enter the second stage of the games,
meeting six ice hockey powerhouses the United States, Sweden, Russia,
Canada, Finland and Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
It opens a new era at the Nagano Olympics, allowing highly-paid
professional ice hockey players for the first time to participate.
</P>
<P>
It seems to be a satire to recall the 11th winter Olympics that
Japan hosted in 1972.
</P>
<P>
26 years ago in Sapporo, the issue of professionalism threatened
briefly to destroy the winter games.
</P>
<P>
The winner at the time was Avery Brundage, the then International
Olympic Committee president and defender of the amateur ethic.
</P>
<P>
Austrian skier Karl Schranz was the loser and he was kicked out of
the games three days after his name and picture was used in commercial
advertising.
</P>
<P>
Since the year 1972, the IOC has changed tack completely, first
deciding to ignore the issue and now encouraging the parcitipation of
professionals.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 Barcelona Summer Olympics, the United States sent a "Dream
Team" to the basketball tournament, and this time, the ice hockey
competitions would become a "Dream Tournament".
</P>
<P>
Canada, the United States, Sweden, Russia, Czech Republic and
Finland all feature NHL players in the games and they all stand good
chance to win the title.
</P>
<P>
For many of the professionals, Olympic gold is still something that
their money cannot buy.
</P>
<P>
"To this day, my Olympic experience was the biggest thrill of my
life," said Canada's Paul Kariya. "Since I was a kid, even more than
playing in the NHL, I wanted to achieve that." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
