<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People in Heilongjiang Become Self-sustaining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 580,000 people in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province last year were able to become
self-sustaining and end their dependence on government relief.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang's poverty-stricken population has been reduced to
1.12 million and marks a significant step in the province's effort
to eliminate absolute poverty by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The people who began to have enough to eat and wear last year
were scattered in 160 poor villages in four counties, according to
a leading provincial official in charge of poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Heilongjiang obtained 320 million yuan in national
special funds for poverty reduction, the largest amount ever. The
province also directed 310 million yuan of local funds to poverty
reduction.
</P>
<P>
The funds were used to improve the infrastructure in
impoverished areas and to implement more than 1,000
poverty-reduction projects.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in 1997 Heilongjiang's 16
poverty-plagued counties reported a combined gross domestic
product of 13.7 billion yuan, up 11 percent over 1996, and a
fiscal income of 800 million yuan, up 13 percent. The per capita
income in the impoverished areas reached 1,500 yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
