<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Per-Capita Residential Space Growing in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The per-capita residential
space in Shanghai reached nine square meters by the end of 1997, a
remarkable increase compared to the early 1980s when it was six
square meters. The improvement was credited to local government
efforts to improve housing conditions for the residents.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai started building residential apartments on a large
scale in the mid-'80s. In the early '90s, the annual completion of
residential buildings surpassed 10 million square meters.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city invested 44.7 billion yuan to build 14.97
million square meters of residential housing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local government has focused on improving living
conditions and building more public facilities for the convenience
of those who have moved into the new residential blocks.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six middle and primary schools and kindergartens were
established in 38 newly built residential blocks in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Shanghai has demolished 2.62 million
square meters of slum housing since 1990 and replaced them with
new buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
