<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Conduct National Population Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will conduct a
nationwide census on population in late August, Nassor Malocho,
the Minister of State in the President's Office announced.
</P>
<P>
Malocho told reporters in Dar es Salaam Friday that the survey
will be carried out from door to door in nine million households
in five days beginning August 30.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative for Tanzania to conduct a national census
this year despite the effects of the current heavy rains caused
by the El Nino phenomenon," he said.
</P>
<P>
If the country does not plan the census, the exact number of
the newborns will not be known, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said those living or traveling outside the
country, and beggars or street children, will also be counted.
</P>
<P>
The national census may cost 5.3 billion Shillings (about 8.3
million U.S. Dollars). The United Nations Fund for Population
and the U.S. government have promised to lend financial or
personnel support to the exercise.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Tanzanian government has spent 500 million
Shillings (783,000 Dollars) on the preparations for the census,
and will spend another 172 million (about 269,000 U.S. Dollars)
this month and 163 million (255,000 Dollars) next month.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's population is estimated at 32 million. The last
census took place in 1988, which found the country had 23 million
people at that time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
