<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Back Home After Trip to ASEAN Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad returned home Saturday after a three-nation tour
of ASEAN to get support for the regional grouping's proposal to
trade in their respective currencies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's visit to Thailand, the Philippines and Singapore
since last Thursday ended on a positive note with Bangkok and
Manila agreeing to implement the proposal mooted at the Second
ASEAN Informal Summit here last December.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir held talks with his Thai counterpart Chuan Leekpai in
Bangkok, and also discussed the proposal with Philippine President
Fidel Ramos and Singapore Premier Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Their talks centered on the need for ASEAN countries to
increase intra-ASEAN trade and the use of regional currencies to
lessen ASEAN's dependence on foreign currencies in intra-group
trading.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir told a news conference at Kuala Lumpur International
Airport that Thailand, the Philippines and Singapore had agreed in
principle to trade using their respective currencies.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposal would be implemented if it is found to be
feasible.
</P>
<P>
"In principle, they have no objections but they will study the
advantages and disadvantages of the Singapore currency being used
as a peg for trade and the use of each own's currencies for the
purpose of trade between ASEAN countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides Malaysia, Thailand, the Philippines and Singapore,
ASEAN's members also include Indonesia, Brunei, Laos, Myanmar and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Several ASEAN currencies have fallen sharply against the U.S.
dollar since Thailand floated the baht last July, triggering off
the regional currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia also offered to host the meeting of
ASEAN bank governors to discuss the proposal.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question as to whether Malaysia was prepared
to serve as the clearing house, Mahathir said the matter would be
decided at the meeting. He added that in this sophisticated age of
information technology, there is no need to have (a clearing
house) in one place because everything will be immediately linked
to any center that is set up.  
</P>
</TEXT>
