<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Use "Environmental Treatment" for Cold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- After years of research, two
Chinese doctors have developed a way to treat the common cold.
</P>
<P>
The doctors place a thermoelectric field around the patient's
head with the temperature slightly higher then the body
temperature. Zhao Yong and Zhang Xiaowei believe that the
thermoelectric field helps speed up circulation in the capillaries
and expansion of the sweat glands, helping a person's "inner
environment for immunity" fight the virus.
</P>
<P>
The doctors call this method an "environmental treatment,"
explaining that just as a bad environment can lead to a cold, good
environments can help cure the disease.
</P>
<P>
"Actually this treatment can be traced to the traditional
Chinese medical theory which views the human body as one
interconnected system and holds that a cold always starts in one's
head," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
The equipment they invented for curing colds is now in pilot
production after being approved by the Beijing Medicine Equipment
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide, the common cold remains a major nemesis for
mankind. British scientists reportedly are researching a vaccine
for all cold viruses. A recent report by a Polish scientist
advised people not to take any medicine immediately after catching
a cold, saying it is better to "fight the cold yourself." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
