<HEADLINE> Chickens Shipped to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A batch of 38,000 live
chickens was shipped to Hong Kong from Shenzhen early this morning
after going through rigid quarantine procedures.
</P>
<P>
The chickens are the first since Hong Kong suspended importing
live chickens in the wake of an outbreak of bird flu on Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
Late Friday night technicians of Guangdong Provincial
Department of Animal and Plant Quarantine were sent to 25
export-oriented chicken farms in the cities of Guangzhou,
Dongguan, Zhuhai and Shenzhen to collect blood samples and
sterilize the chickens.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 blood samples were collected randomly from each
group of 3,000 live chickens, double the amount required by the
Agriculture and Fisheries Department of Hong Kong. All the samples
passed the examinations, said Jiang Zhijian, general manager of
Jiangcun Chicken Farm of Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of bird flu, quarantine departments in
Guangdong have collected 10,000 blood samples from 200 poultry
farms to test for the H5N1 virus. All tests were negative.
</P>
<P>
Late last month the World Health Organization concluded, after
a week of investigation by 14 of its experts, that the bird flu
did not originate in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland used to export an average 100,000 live
chickens daily to Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
