<HEADLINE> Pro-Iraqi Rally Turns Violent in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 7 (Xinhua) -- At least five people were
injured Saturday when a pro-Iraqi demonstration held by
Palestinian protesters in the West Bank city of Bethlehem quickly
turned into clash with Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
About 500 Palestinians, mainly teenagers, took part in the
demonstration to show support to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
and protest the United States' threat to use force against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Holding high Saddam's portraits and Iraqi flags, chanting
anti-American and anti-Israeli slogans, the protesters marched
toward Rachel's tomb, the Jewish holy site just at the entrance
to the city.
</P>
<P>
When they approached near the tomb, some began throwing stones
at Israeli soldiers guarding the site, who fired tear gas and
rubber bullets in response.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service Jerusalem Media
and Communications Center reported that at least five people,
including a Palestinian policeman and a Palestinian reporter,
were wounded by rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, there have been several such clashes near
Rachel's tomb, signaling the rise of tension between Israelis and
Palestinians at a time when the peace process is deeply deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accuse U.S. President Bill Clinton of
adopting double standards in dealing with the Iraqi crisis over
weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that while Clinton threatens to use force to
demand Iraq's compliance with United Nations Security Council
resolutions, he did nothing to pressure Israel to honor the U.N.
resolutions that request Israeli withdrawal from occupied Arab
territories.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain threatened to launched air strike on Iraq
if diplomacy failed to secure U.N. weapons inspectors' "full and
free" access to Iraqi presidential palaces where illegal arms are
suspected of being hidden. 
</P>
