<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Production Means Circulation Undergoing Fundamental Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The production means
circulation sector in China has experienced fundamental changes
since reforms were carried out a few years ago, according to a
senior government official.
</P>
<P>
At a national working conference held today on goods and
materials, Vice-Minister of Internal Trade Lu Jiang said that,
because of the reforms, the production means circulation sector is
proceeding steadily in conjunction with the construction of a
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Lu said one big change is that the circulation of production
means has gradually shifted from state planning to market
regulation, and market mechanisms have begun to play a fundamental
role in distributing resources.
</P>
<P>
With the emergence of a buyers' market, prices for production
means have been gradually declining, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the operation of production means is no
longer monopolized by state-owned circulation enterprises, and the
market is becoming increasingly competitive. The style, scope and
content of production means management have undergone intensive
changes as a result of reforms in the administrative departments
of this sector.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that reforms on the production means circulation system
and state-owned goods and materials enterprises will be further
accelerated this year to better support national economic
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fish Stunted in C. Uganda Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nile tilapia, a common
fish existing in Ugandan lakes, has been stunted in the recent
years, an environment report said.
</P>
<P>
A matured Nile tilapia usually has a size of 50 cm in Uganda
waters. But in Lake Wamala in central Uganda, it was stunted to
32 cm in 1970s and 22 cm by 1990s and now 14 cm, according to The
New Vision paper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing and environment degradation are the main cause for
the stunt, said a bi-annual report launched by the National
Management Authority.
</P>
<P>
Fish catching increased from 1,000 tons in 1960 to 7,100 tons
in 1967 and decreased to about 1,000 tons since, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The environment degradation in Lake Wamala is caused by the
decrease of water poured into the lake and serious siltation
which resulted in shrinkage of areas in the lake, an earlier
report noted. The lake now witnesses an overcrowding of fishes,
it added.
</P>
<P>
Lake Wamala originally had impoverished indigenous fishes such
as mamba and male. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0102 </DOCNO>
