<HEADLINE> HK Promotes Use of IT in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A series of three-minute TV
programs will be broadcast in Hong Kong from Sunday to promote the
use of information technology (IT) in education.
</P>
<P>
The series of three-minute episodes, which interview Education
Department officials, school principals, teachers, parents and
students, will stress the importance and popularity of IT in daily
living and explain the government's IT policy in education.
</P>
<P>
The series is part of the "Classrooms of the 21st Century
Scheme" jointly organized by the Education Department of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region of China, the Lions Club of
Metropolitan Hong Kong and the Lions Club of Castle Peak.
</P>
<P>
The scheme was launched on November 21, 1997 to encourage and
assist teachers in using IT as a tool to further improve the
quality of education in the classroom. The activities will extend
over a period of six months.
</P>
<P>
A more elaborate TV program on IT in education featuring plays
and games will also be broadcast on February 27.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a total of 405 nominations were received from
schools to participate in the "Workshop on Classrooms of the 21st
Century Scheme" which is being conducted from January 5 to March
20 in six classes.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that the workshops will help teachers equip
themselves with the necessary IT skills to design creative
teaching materials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, schools are invited to participate in the Multimedia
Educational Materials Design Competition which is also part of the
"Classrooms of the 21st Century Scheme".
</P>
<P>
The competition aims at encouraging teachers to apply IT in
developing educational software.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition on IT in education will be conducted on April 25
and 26 at Hong Kong Industrial Technology Center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
