<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Lights Up With 100,000 Lanterns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, capital of east
China's Jiangsu Province, has been lighted with more than 100,000
colorful lanterns.
</P>
<P>
It is a tradition for Chinese to hang lanterns in front of
their houses or in the streets during the Chinese Lunar New Year's
Day "Spring Festival" and the Lantern Festival, which falls on
Feb. 11 this year.
</P>
<P>
The lanterns are made of paper, wire and bamboo and have many
patterns resembling animals, flowers or other things. Many Chinese
believe that to hang lanterns of different colors and patterns in
the festivals brings fortunes in the new year.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing is one of old capital cities in China, which was
capital for 10 dynasties. It is also one of the major lantern
producers and markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
Many local families are good at making lanterns, passing their
skills from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
Li Guixian, 72, is one of the most famous lantern makers in the
city, who has been engaged in the traditional handicraft work for
50 years.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, there were a large number of patterns," Li
said. "It is a pity that many old patterns of lanterns have been
lost." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes U.S. Charges on China's Religious Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- The charges leveled by the
U.S. State Department's "1997 Human Rights Report" against China's
religious status are totally baseless and utterly unjustifiable, a
visiting Chinese official said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ye Xiaowen, director of the Religious Bureau of the Chinese
State Council, told a press conference that the U.S.
accusation that the Chinese government undertakes religious
control and persecution is wrong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese citizens enjoy freedom of religious belief, which
is enshrined as a basic right in China's Constitution, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978 when China began to implement the policies of reform
and opening, the country has devoted itself not only to developing
economy and raising people's living standards but also to
improving the democratic and legal systems and ensuring citizens'
rights including the freedom of religious belief, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Now there are more than 100 million religious believers in
China, Ye said. The number of Christian believers in the country,
has increased to 10 million from 700,000 in 1949 when the new
China was founded.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, about 20 million copies of the Bible
were published with tax exemption in China, Ye said. In the 1990s,
about 600 Christian churches were built annually in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official pointed out that what has been cited in
the U.S. State Department human rights report is based, as it has
always been before, on rumors, distortion, fabrication and
imagination.
</P>
<P>
Giving an example, Ye quoted the report as saying that a
Chinese regulation requires all religious bodies to register at
the National Religious Bureau and subjects them to the supervision
of an official religious organization.
</P>
<P>
In fact, China does not have such a law or regulation, Ye noted.
</P>
<P>
As a social body, a Chinese religious organization is
registered in China's civil administration departments, Ye
said. And there is no official religious organization in China.
</P>
<P>
Ye rejected the allegation by the U.S. report that a major
church in Zhejiang Province was banned last year by a local
government, saying the allegation was completely groundless.
</P>
<P>
Ye said it is also a sheer fabrication in the report which said
religious sites can be registered in China on condition that
owners of the sites join the Three Self-Patriotic Movement
Committee of the Protestant Churches of China and the Christian
Council of China.
</P>
<P>
China's relevant laws and regulations have no such provision,
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes U.S. Charges on China's Religious Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to the accusation that Xu Yongze was sentenced to
ten years' imprisonment in September, 1997 due to missionary work,
Ye said the fact is that Xu had urged his followers to shout and
cry unrestrainedly for several consecutive days. As a result, many
people abandoned their jobs, some went blind due to longish cry
and some even committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
Xu was convicted of doing harm to society in violation of
Chinese laws and sentenced to three years' imprisonment by a local
court.
</P>
<P>
Ye said the U.S. report provided some specific examples, trying
to prove the existence of religious persecution by the Chinese
government. This is unjustifiable. People like Xu Yongze were
prosecuted because of their violation of laws not because of their
involvement in religious activities.
</P>
<P>
The principles of China's judiciary are based on facts, Ye
said. Everyone is equal before the law. Any person, whether
religious or not, will be prosecuted if he breaks the law. And
there is nothing to blame about that, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is well-known that there are more prisoners in U.S. than in
China. And the American prisoners who are religious greatly
outnumber their Chinese counterparts. Based on the logic of the
report, does that mean that the U.S. government is exercising
religion persecution?
</P>
<P>
Ye went on to urge the U.S. government to stop interfering with
China's internal affairs by fabrications about China's religious
issues.
</P>
<P>
He said only the people have the best understanding of their
nation and are the most qualified to speak on its affairs; and the
human rights should be developed by efforts of the nation's own
people and government. The United States has no right whatever to
dictate other countries' internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
China is in favor of exchanges of visits and dialogue in order
to deepen understanding, build common ground and promote friendly
relations between the two countries, Ye said. At the same time, it
disapproves of any act of accusation and interference with other
countries' internal affairs through fabrication and distortion.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press conference were Chairman of the
Christian Council of China Dr. Han Wenzao and Vice Chairman of
Three-Self Patriotic Movement Committee of the Protestant Churches
of China Deng Fucun.
</P>
<P>
The delegation came to the United States for a visit on January
29 at the invitation of American religious leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
