<HEADLINE> Nigeria Plans Water Scheme for Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's military government
will launch a small town water scheme to boost the standard of
living in rural areas before handing over in October, the Daily
Time reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot scheme has been designed by the government to serve
town and villages with a population of at least 2,000, the
national newspaper quoted Minister of Water Resources and Rural
Development Alhaji Abubakar Sakwa as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the scheme is expected to serve the
interests of some communities which could not benefit from the
federal and state governments' water projects over the years.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will involve the Petroleum Trust Fund, which is set
up by the government with money collected from the rise of fuel
prices to specifically fund infrastructure project throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The investment in the water scheme has not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Lack of safe water in rural areas, where more than 70 percent
of Nigeria's 100 million-strong population live, has been a
source of various diseases for local dwellers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
