<HEADLINE> Kuwait Imports Gas Masks, Anticipating Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has imported about
50,000 gas masks from Egypt over the weekend in preparation for a
possible Iraqi chemical attack, local media reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Times quoted defense sources as saying that Kuwait did
so in order to protect its population against any Iraqi chemical
attack.
</P>
<P>
The masks will be used for emergency teams, volunteers and
other government bodies instead of being given to the ordinary
people, according to sources from the Kuwaiti Interior
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti National Assembly decided to hold a closed-door
extraordinary meeting Saturday on the recent developments during
which parliamentary members are expected to call on the government
to import more gas masks for Kuwaiti population.
</P>
<P>
Many people in Kuwait fear that Baghdad might attack the small
neighbor if the U.S. and Britain launched a military strike to
force Iraqi compliance in the current Iraq-U.N. standoff over
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has put its small armed forces on a higher level of
alert and deployed "Patriot" missiles in strategic places in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the U.S. has asked Saudi Arabia to
allow Americans staying in Kuwait to cross the borders into the
kingdom without the need to obtain visas in case the current
Iraq-U.N. standoff develops into a military confrontation,
informed sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have been intensifying pressure on
Baghdad to allow the U.N. inspectors unimpeded access to suspect
sites to search for banned weapons to avoid a "substantial" or
"robust" attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
