<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Implement Bilateral Payment Arrangement to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian deputy prime
minister Anwar Ibrahim said Saturday that a bilateral payment
arrangement (BPA) will be implemented to further enhance
intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism would also promote the use of currencies of
member countries in the transactions, Anwar, who is also finance
minister, told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad is currently on a
tour of Thailand, the Philippines and Singapore to hold talks with
leaders of these ASEAN members on regional economic developments
and on ways to promote intra-ASEAN trade using regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, Thailand and the Philippines have agreed to use their
respective currency to reduce the dependence on the U.S. dollar
for their mutual trade.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said a committee comprising the relevant ministries had
been formed to draw up a list of commodities Malaysia could export
to the other ASEAN countries and items it could import from them.
</P>
<P>
"I do not foresee too many complications as this should be
easily implemented based on our experience with Singapore," he
said. "We are using both ringgit and the Singapore dollar although
it is pegged to the U.S. dollar. We import in Singapore dollars,
and they import in ringgit."
</P>
<P>
"That is a good beginning for the other ASEAN countries to look
at...a good model although it can be improved," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
The BPA is considered as only a small instrument, he said.
"But, in the context of creating more opportunities for
intra-ASEAN trade, we will proceed with the BPA."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said efforts to further enhance intra-ASEAN trade should
be taken as agreement on the matter had been reached.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
