<P>
LAGOS, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A leading Nigerian paper said
Saturday there might be a British connection behind nigeria's
alleged coup plot last December, noting that seven of the coup
suspects had got British visas days before they were arrested.
</P>
<P>
This Day reported that Nigerian security agents found out
during the search of the suspects' residences that seven of them
have their passports stamped with British visas.
</P>
<P>
Among the seven is Lieutenant-general Oldipo Diya,
Vice-chairman of the Provisional Ruling Council and Nigeria's
number two leader after head of state General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
It took place, said the report, despite the fact that Britain,
together with most western countries, is now maintaining a visa
sanctions on Nigerian government officials, especially on its
military officers.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed in 1993 after the then Babangida
military government of Nigeria annulled the June 12, 1993
presidential election. It was strengthened in 1995 after the
Abacha government hanged nine minority activists for murders.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the coup plot was discovered last December, the
Nigerian government alleged that some foreign governments were
involved in the coup plot.
</P>
<P>
Another evidence of British connection with the coup plot, the
report said, is that British High Commissioner Graham Burton was
not invited to Nigerian capital Abuja to watch the video and
audio tapes showing activities of the coup plotters.
</P>
<P>
The tapes, believed to be taken by secret agents, were widely
shown to the diplomatic corps, including U.S. Ambassador Willian
Twaddel.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commission in Lagos, however, has denied the
issue of visas to the coup suspects. In a fax to the newspaper
it said, "the United Kingdom implements these restrictions (visa
bans) rigorously."
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government announced the discovery of the alleged
coup plot on December 21, 1997, claiming that Diya and 11 other
senior military officers had planned to violently overthrow the
government of General Abacha.
</P>
<P>
A special panel has reportedly completed its investigation
into the coup plot and the suspects are expected soon to appear
before a military court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
