<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT February 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine and Turkey signed an agreement on the defense
of the Black Sea coast on Thursday to boost cooperation in the
fight against organized crime, the Ukrainian Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement said the two sides would take all measures
necessary, including the use of coast guardsmen, to eliminate
crimes such as arms smuggling, drug trafficking and the illegal
sale of cultural relics. Ukraine and Turkey will establish a joint
commission to coordinate their operation against anti-maritime
crimes, said the document. (Ukraine-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's House of Representatives (lower house) passed
two key bills Saturday which will pave the way for the use of 30
trillion yen (about 241.9 billion U.S. dollars) in public funds to
help restore trust in the country's troubled financial system.
</P>
<P>
The bills cleared the lower house's plenary session with the
support of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its two
non-cabinet allies, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New
Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The bills were immediately sent to the House of Councillors, or
upper house. (Japan-Financial-Bills)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said that his
country is opposed to separatist movements in Kosovo province, but
called on Yugoslavia to grant a high degree of autonomy to ethnic
Albanians in the province.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who is on a brief visit to Albania, talked with
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano and Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo on the Kosovo issue and German-Albanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which is
attempting to seek independence from Yugoslavia. (Albania-Germany)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said Friday that he
sees violation of law in a fatal cable car accident involving a
U.S. military jet on Tuesday, in which 20 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister said that his government is not
questioning Italy's membership of NATO or friendship with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Twenty people were killed when a U.S. Marine EA-6B electronic
warfare plane sliced a cable line with its tail fin in northern
Italy Tuesday, sending a cable car and the 20 people aboard
plunging to their death.The accident has sparked anti-Americanism
and anti-military sentiment in Italy. (Italy-Cable Car
Accident-Consequences)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
