<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Malaysia to Use Local Currencies in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
announced here Saturday that his country and Malaysia have agreed
on a payment scheme that will allow them to use their currencies
in conducting bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Ramos said that the move was aimed
at easing the Southeast Asian region's demand for U.S. dollars and
enabling the two countries to speed up their full recovery from
the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that the agreement was reached during his talks with
visiting Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The present financial and currency situation in the region was
the main focus of our discussion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that he and Mahathir also reaffirmed their common
thrust to step up tourism and trade relations between their
countries to help shore up the region's economies and attain full
recovery from the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"To promote the expansion of intra-ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) trade and tourism, Prime Minister
Mahathir and I agreed to facilitate the use of the Philippine peso
and the Malaysian ringgit in Philippine-Malaysian bilateral
trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We instructed our respective officials, in coordination with
the private sector, to develop the appropriate mechanism to
implement this payment arrangement," Ramos added.
</P>
<P>
He said that both countries are confident that East Asia will
recover from the financial turbulence sweeping the region.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived here Friday afternoon for an overnight working
visit and left Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
