<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian MPs Call for Withdrawing Benefits from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Parliament members of Zambia's
ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) have called on the
government to withdraw retirement benefits from former President
Kenneth Kaunda because of his active political activities.
</P>
<P>
In parliament debate on Friday the MPs urged the government to
amend the Former President Act and review Kaunda's status because
he has continued enjoying the benefits when he is still active in
politics, Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted David Shimonde as saying that the
funding should be withheld because Kaunda is allegedly using the
same money to fight the government.
</P>
<P>
"It is like arming your enemy because this man is using the
same money we give him to fight us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another MP, Jeston Mulando, urged parliament leader,
Vice-president Christon Tembo to initiate the amendment of the
Former President Act before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
MP Francis Kamanga said a law should be passed to disqualify
former heads of state from receiving benefits under the act if
they committed a serious crime or resumed active politics.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said the government has no immediate plans
to either scrap the office of former president or stop funding it
because if wants to maintain the political tradition.
</P>
<P>
National Assembly Chairman of Committees Frederick Hapunda
cautioned parliament members against discussing Kaunda because he
is not in the house to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
The government said last September that Kaunda had received
about 183,000 U.S. Dollars in retirement benefits since 1991,
when he was defeated in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested on December 25, 1997 in alleged connection
with the October 28 abortive coup and transferred six days later
from prison to house arrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
