<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Reiterates No Change in Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Saturday Malaysia's policy of tight
credit control will remain.
</P>
<P>
The statement by Anwar, who is also finance minister, came
after the announcement Friday by the State Bank that it would
reduce Statutory Reserve Requirement (SRR) of financial
institutions to 10 percent from the current 13.5 percent effective
from February 16, 1998, and various reports on the public asking
the government to ease its monetary stance.
</P>
<P>
The reduction would release about 14 billion ringgit (3.636
billion U.S. dollars) in funds to banking institutions, but is not
aimed at providing additional liquidity to the system, the bank
said in a statement, adding the reduction was aimed at enhancing
the efficiency of the intermediation process.
</P>
<P>
"This measure by no means would alter our original credit
plan," Anwar told a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The target credit growth of 15 percent at the end of
1998 still remains. There is no change in the credit plan target
announced earlier."
</P>
<P>
"We are suggesting a credit growth of 15 percent. We are not
suggesting a credit squeeze as perceived by some quarters, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar called on the public to appreciate the importance of
having to have tight credit controls.
</P>
<P>
He said the public would have to recognize that everybody in
the country including companies and the economy were having a
problem in the wake of the regional financial turmoil since last
July.
</P>
<P>
"If you do not learn and appreciate and recognize that we have
a problem, then we will have more problems. Better recognize that
we actually have a problem now, and we have to judiciously and
prudently manage our affairs. Of course, we, the government, will
do everything possible to assist the companies, we have to
appreciate that we have to deal with the present problem and do
not give a wrong message both to the investors or to the markets,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said financial institutions were "very cautious" in giving
out loans for all economic activities, "which is good and
reasonable, but we have told them to ease it."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the government recognized the pressures on the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the strength of Malaysia's
financial system has been the ability of the banks to prudently
manage their own affairs with some guidelines given.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think I would like to jeopardize that now," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
