<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Laid-off Women Workers Choose Household Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Sheng Rong, a former assistant
engineer, had never thought of losing her job or becoming a
part-time household worker.
</P>
<P>
However, Sheng said she is so satisfied with her job that she
does it wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
There are 3,000 trained household workers in Shanghai, a
leading industrial and commercial city of China. Most of these
workers were laid off from enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Labor listed household services as an
official occupation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 laid-off female workers in Shanghai had
attended training courses on household services in 1997 run by the
local women's federation and the labor bureau.
</P>
<P>
These training courses include ethics and etiquette training,
skills for handling household chores, maintaining safety in
apartments, and traditions and customs.
</P>
<P>
To encourage more laid-off female workers to do this job, the
women's committee of local trade unions launched a program to
honor outstanding workers.
</P>
<P>
Experts here pointed out that Shanghai has 4.4 million families
which means 44,000 working posts if one out of 100 local
households needs just one household worker.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, over 10,000 families of foreigners are also eager to
employ high-quality household workers, the labor ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
