<HEADLINE> Chinese People Older at First Marriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Residents in China's capital of
Beijing were the oldest among all first married people across the
country as they first wedded at an average age of 26.16.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai couples followed Beijing couples with an average age
of 25.73.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics based on 1996 data showed that Chinese men
were 1.99 years older, women 0.69 years older when they married
for the first time compared with 1990 data.
</P>
<P>
The average age of first married people in China was 24.02 in
1996. The men's average age for the first marriage was 25.77, and
women's, 22.75.
</P>
<P>
Besides Beijing and Shanghai, the first marriage age surpassed
24 in south China's Guangdong Province and Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, east China's Zhejiang, Shandong and Fujian
provinces, Tianjin Municipality, and central China's Hunan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The figure in Tibet, northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region and Qinghai Province, and southwest China's Sichuan
Province was below 23.
</P>
<P>
According to a sampling of nationwide population changes, in
1990 about 8.55 million people married before they reached legal
ages -- 22 for men and 20 for women in China.
</P>
<P>
The number of early married people dropped by three fourths,
however, to 2.17 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the average age of first marriage changed
as a result of economic development, because economic and social
development has immediate impact on people's idea about marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
