<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Remains as China's Third Largest Trade Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- China's trade with the United
States witnessed an annual average increase of 22.6 percent in the
1990s, soaring from 11.77 billion US dollars in 1990 to 48.99
billion dollars in 1997, according to statistics released by
China's General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth of China's total export and import in the
same period was 15.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year's trade with US rose 14.3 percent from the 1996
figure, with exports going up 22.5 percent to reach 32.69 billion
dollars, and imports 0.9 percent, 16.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of China's trade with the U.S. to China's total
foreign trade reached a record high of 15.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
About 38 percent of the trade between the two countries was
conducted via Hong Kong
</P>
<P>
The processing trade grew 23 percent to shoot at 28.4
billion dollars last year, accounting for 58 percent of the
bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
General trade also rose 5.5 percent over the previous year,
totaling 15.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's state-owned enterprises did 23.55 billion dollars worth
of business with the U.S., and foreign-funded ones, 24.46 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Export of machinery and electronic products to the United
States grew 26.5 percent to hit 13.04 billion dollars, that of
labor-intensive commodities also increased.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, import of resources or technology-intensive
commodities from the U.S. expanded in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
