<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Gets Loan from African Export-Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The African Export-Import Bank
(AFREXIMBANK) Friday provided a 380-million-Zimbabwean Dollar (27
million U.S. Dollars) credit finance facility to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Companies operating in the country's Export Processing Zones
(EPZ) could soon start benefiting from the credit facility with
the aim of boosting export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony here in the capital, EPZ
General Manager Walter Chidhakwa said the development of an
export oriented economy was central to Zimbabwe's growth as it
will enhance export earnings and create thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Increase in exports could also help the country improve its
reserves which sent importers into a panic leading to the
historical crash of the Zimbabwean Dollar against major
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The country's balance of payment which has also been operating
at a deficit could also stabilize in the long run.
</P>
<P>
AFREXIMBANK President Christopher Eduardo said his bank was
putting its weight on EPZ projects to enhance their
competitiveness in the world market and make more significant
their impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of Africa's exports are raw materials and out
of these, 80 percent are shipped to Europe and the United States
of America. Unfortunately, 70 percent of the continent's exports
are made in the fourth quarter of the year making the continent
vulnerable to the dangers of concentrated activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These concentrations have been largely blamed for the
economic difficulties the continent faces as it increases the
economic risk usually associated with highly concentrated
activities," said Eduardo.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to the Zimbabwean EPZ, we are glad to note that
the projects already approved are the right kind... In our
opinion we will achieve the desired results and that is why we
are very pleased to be associated with it," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
