<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Committed to Fighting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae has reaffirmed his government's commitment to eradicating
corruption, saying everybody must contribute to fighting the vice
in public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Kenya Times Saturday quoted him as saying that
corruption was an impediment to investment and growth and every
effort must not be spared to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
He told an economic seminar ended Friday that corruption was
the greatest disease interfering with the management of resources
in Kenya, adding, it was his wish that everybody involved be
dealt with regardless of social status.
</P>
<P>
The country's economy is drifting dangerously into the control
of corrupt operatives who are denying the government billions of
Shillings through tax evasion, he noted.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, Kenya loses 9 billion Kenyan Shillings
(about 150 million U.S. Dollars) in revenue earnings from the
Mombasa port to a corrupt cartel through tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that Kenya's economy was threatened and
could not achieve meaningful growth unless people involved in
economic crimes were prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar organized by the Institute of Certified
Public Accounts of Kenya was also attended by high ranking
officials from the European Union and other donors. 
</P>
