<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of the
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber, resuming trading
Tuesday after a week-long festive holiday period, closed the week
lower due to stronger local currency versus the greenback.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market, February South ended the week at
2,265 ringgit (588.31 U.S. dollars) per ton, down 325 ringgit
(84.41 dollars) from the previous week's close of 2,590 ringgit
(672.72 dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals price eased due to stronger ringgit versus
the greenback. The ringgit rallied to close the week, the first in
the Year of the Tiger at a high of 3.8300/8700 to the dollar
against 4.4350/4700 at the previous trading week's close.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals trading is likely to move in tandem with the
performance of the ringgit against the dollar next week, a dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
The currency factor also had impact on the Kuala Lumpur Tin
Market (KLTM) this week.
</P>
<P>
The tin price ended the week lower to 20.20 ringgit (5.24
dollars) per kg from 23.26 ringgit (6.04 dollars) at last week's
close.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover stood at 287 tons with the local, European
and Japanese buyers taking up the bulk of the transaction against
last week's turnover of 165 tons.
BAC074WSA003S07PAQL15:3515:350217
</P>
<P>
The currency factor is likely to determine the direction of the
tin price on the local market next week also, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
