<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Congress Passes New Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Congress passed
a compromise version of the new oil deregulation bill late Friday
night, clearing the last hurdle for the country to exit from
decades of economic supervision by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
The new bill, concluded earlier by a bicameral congressional
committee after more than one month of bickering, will replace the
old oil deregulation law after being signed by President Fidel
Ramos within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The old oil deregulation law, which took effect in February
1997, was nullified by the Supreme Court last November on the
grounds that it violated the constitutional prohibition of
monopolies and unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
The old law provided for a seven percent tariff for refined
petroleum products, and a three percent tariff for crude oil, to
encourage firms to invest in the domestic refinery industry.
</P>
<P>
But the Supreme Court ruled that forcing firms to choose
between investing huge amounts in refineries and paying higher
tariffs amounted to a restriction on free trade and violated the
intention of the law.
</P>
<P>
Under the new oil deregulation bill, a uniform tariff of three
percent will be imposed on both imported crude and refined oil
products.
</P>
<P>
The new bill also sets up a 2.9 billion pesos (72.5 million
U.S. dollars) buffer fund to subsidize oil companies during a
five-month transition period before the full deregulation of the
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The final Congressional passage of the new oil bill was hailed
by both the government and the business community since it will
enable the country to graduate from the IMF's decades-long
tutelage and help the downstream oil industry attract more
investments.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia said
the new bill would strengthen foreign investors' confidence in the
country's economy by allowing its graduation from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, which has been under the IMF economic
supervision since the late 1960s, was supposed to graduate from
the IMF before the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
But the graduation was delayed due to the annulment of the old
oil deregulation law, one of the vital economic structure reform
measures required by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Under the old oil deregulation law, the government would no
longer regulate the oil industry and the country's three major oil
firms can adjust oil prices without seeking government approval.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the oil industry's deregulation allowed the
government to withdraw its huge subsidy to the industry and helped
the government improve its fiscal position.
</P>
<P>
The abolishment of the old oil law gave rise to wide concern
among the business community, particularly foreign oil firms, over
the country's investment environment and the government's fiscal
position.
</P>
<P>
Many new players in the local oil industry reportedly
threatened earlier to close operations and put on hold new
investments in the country if the passage of the new oil bill was
further delayed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
Oil companies also complained that they were losing money
because they could not hike oil prices even in face of a regional
financial turmoil in which the Philippine peso has depreciated by
54 percent against the U.S. dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0151 </DOCNO>
