<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Human Bodies Retrieved at Philippine Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Six more cadaver bags of human
bodies were retrieved from the crash site of the ill-fated flight
387 in Mt. Sumagaya Saturday morning, bringing to 13 the total
cadaver bags delivered to Cagayan de Oro city, Mindanao, for
forensic examination.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Cagayan de Oro, Jesus Dureza, head of
the Presidential Action Center (PAC), which supervises the search
and rescue operations, said that retrieval operations were
temporarily deferred Saturday morning due to cloud buildup in the
crash site of the Cebu Pacific aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The DC-9 plane carrying 104 people, including five crew
members, crashed Monday morning on its way from Manila to Cagayan
de Oro.
</P>
<P>
Dureza said elements of the Composite Air Support Force (CASF)
composed of helicopters are now on standby at Mat-i in Claveria,
Misamis Oriental province, waiting for further orders.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to resume operations anytime this afternoon if the
weather condition improves in the area," Dureza said, adding that
a bigger helicopter landing pad had been cleared 200 meters from
the crash site.
</P>
<P>
As the bodies were badly mutilated, it was impossible to tell
how many bodies have been found, rescuers said.
</P>
<P>
It will take longer time to recover the remains of the victims
because a landslide caused by the impact of the plane has buried
most of passengers. Around 20 bags of bodies have been found since
the search and rescue operations started Monday.
</P>
<P>
Retrieved cadaver bags composed of fragments of body parts of
crash victims are now also undergoing segregation in Cagayan de
Oro by foreign forensic experts backed by the National Bureau of
Investigation (NBI).
</P>
<P>
Identities of the victims remain unavailable as search and
rescue operations continue on its sixth day Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary Carlos Tanega of the Air Transport Office (ATO)
said that aviation investigators have started to analyze the
probable cause of Cebu Pacific Airways flight 387 crash following
recovery of some aircraft parts in the area.
</P>
<P>
Tanega said they are looking into many angles such as
instrument error and pilot lapses as possible cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
He said a group of ATO investigators had been sent to the crash
site Saturday morning, hoping to locate the "black box" which
could possibly lead investigators to the cause of the tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
