<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) was bullish this week as the local currency, the
ringgit, began to regain lost ground against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
For the week, after the spectacular rally in terms of gains and
volume Tuesday, market retreated on profit-taking Wednesday
before rebounding over the next two days as the firmer ringgit and
stronger regional bourses renewed investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit rallied to close the first week of trading in the
Year of the Tiger at a high of 3.8300/8700 to the U.S. dollar
against 4.4350/4700 at the previous trading week's close.
</P>
<P>
The 100-stocks benchmark Composite Index ended the week 158.68
points higher at 728.19 compared with 569.51 at the close of the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
The all Main Board Emas Index rose 43.34 points to 186.53 from
143.19, the Industrial Index added 195.52 points to 1,350.37 from
1,155.85 while the Second Board Index added 37.32 points to 189.46
from 152.14.
</P>
<P>
The four-day grand total turnover stood at 3,663 billion shares
valued at 9.077 billion ringgit (2.3576 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board turnover was at 3.329 billion shares valued at
8.194 billion ringgit (864.675 million U.S. dollars) and the
second board turnover was 297.636 million shares valued at 701.562
million ringgit (182.223 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deal this week amounted to 36.121 million shares
valued at 81.802 million ringgit (21.247 million U.S. dollars)
compared with 10.618 million valued at 27.452 million ringgit
(7.130 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Two counters -- Autoair Holdings Bhd which manufactures motor
vehicles related components and accessories and Serisar
Industries, a timber products manufacturer -- were listed on the
second board this week.
</P>
<P>
With the strong buying interest, the two newly-listed counters
received good response from investors this week.
</P>
<P>
Autoair Holdings Bhd made a 30-sen premium when it opened at
3.30 ringgit on its debut Wednesday and the counter ended the week
at 5.35 ringgit while Serisar Industries which was listed Thursday
commanded a 40-sen premium on its debut and closed the week at
5.25 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
On sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 196.714
million shares traded in main board normal market, industrial
products 238.219 million shares, construction 538.270 million
shares, trading/services 715.359 million shares, finance 726.302
million shares, hotels 15.170 million shares, properties 381.977
million shares, plantations 121.155 million shares, mining 33.152
million shares, trusts 2.378 million shares, closed-end fund 1.972
million shares, loan stocks 138.132 million shares, TSR/warrants
190.578 million shares and trading rights 7.461 million shares.
</P>
<P>
On Second Board, consumer products accounted for 59.699 million
shares traded, industrial products 100.424 million shares,
construction 60.171 million shares, trading/services 37.877
million shares, finance 1.783 million shares, loans 518,500 shares
and TSR/warrants 37.163 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market would stay steady over the next week on
the firmer ringgit and as the regional bourses recover.  
</P>
