<HEADLINE> New Ministers Appointed in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister
Victor Ciorbea named replacements on Friday for five ministers and
a secretary who quit the coalition government last week.
</P>
<P>
The rift between Ciorbea's National Peasants' Party (NPP) and
the Democratic Party (DP), the top two powers in the coalition,
became larger in recent weeks as the DP asked Ciorbea to step down.
</P>
<P>
The DP withdrew its ministers from Ciorbea's cabinet on January
29 saying it would only back the government in parliament provided
it agreed to a new program to speed up economic reform.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to fill the vacancy, the NPP met with other coalition
parties and decided to appoint NPP's Constantin Dudu Ionescu,
Romulus Tomescu and Ioan Muresan as ministers of defense,
environment and parliamentary relations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anton Ionescu and Mihai Sorin Stanescu from the
Liberal Party were named as transport minister and defense
secretary.
</P>
<P>
Horia Ene from the Romanian Alternative Party was made minister
for research and technology.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say that without the support of the DP, the
current ruling coalition, which is headed by the NPP, will lose
majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
So far, the DP said it would temporarily maintain its
cooperation with other coalition parties in the parliament, but it
would not support the government "unconditionally". 
</P>
