<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Lower House Passes Two Financial Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives
(lower house) passed two key bills Saturday which will pave the
way for the use of 30 trillion yen (about 241.9 billion
U.S. dollars) in public funds to help restore trust in the
country's troubled financial system.
</P>
<P>
The bills cleared the lower house's plenary session with the
support of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and its two
non-cabinet allies, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New
Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The bills were immediately sent to the House of Councillors, or
upper house.
</P>
<P>
The government and the LDP are seeking enactment of the bills
by the end of next week to restore trust in the banking sector and
revitalize the country's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
One of the bills allocates 17 trillion yen (about 137.1 billion
dollars) in public money to strengthen the Deposit Insurance
Corp. (DIC) to enable the government-backed banking safety net to
cope swiftly with the collapse of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The other bill channels 13 trillion yen (about 104.8 billion
dollars) in public funds to enable DIC to purchase preferred
stocks and bonds to be issued by banks.
</P>
<P>
The step is aimed at helping to strengthen banks' capital bases
and enabling them to extend loans to companies without threatening
their capital-adequacy ratios.
</P>
<P>
Japanese banks have been under fire in connection with the
country's recent credit crunch. They are perceived as being
reluctant to extend loans ahead of the Finance Ministry's
imposition in April of tougher capital adequacy requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Technology Used at Opening Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A new high technology called
Time Lag Adjuster (TLA) was used at the Opening Ceremony of the 18th
Olympic Winter Games here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, the choruses in five locations on five continents
around the world (in Berlin, Sydney, New York, Beijing and Cape Point
of South Africa) was linked under conductor Seiji Ozawa. The singers
followed the maestro's baton via broadcast satellite image, projected
from Nagano.
</P>
<P>
In conventional satellite broadcasting, the delay in transmission
time due to the huge distances between the five locations would
generate a two-way time lag of up to four seconds. This discrepancy
would make it impossible for the choirs to perform as one group.
</P>
<P>
In order to solve the problem, various technologies, including TLA,
were developed. Using the technique of delaying all the images
to match the image with the greatest time lag, the Time Lag Adjuster
reconciles the differences in timing between Nagano and five locations
around the globe and sends a reconstructed coherent transmission to
the performers in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
The Time Lag Adjuster utilizes technology first developed for the
Skip Back Recorder. This Skip Back Recorder equipment was located in
NHK's Kobe broadcasting station and transmitted to the world the
shocking images of the moment that the Great Hanshin Earthquake struck
in the early hours of January 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The principle used by the Skip Back Recorder is to continuously
record images from the cameras and to constantly play back the images
recorded several seconds previously, as if the images had been delayed
by a predetermined amount of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
