<HEADLINE> Germany Opposes Separatist Movements in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, February 6 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said that his country is opposed to separatist movements in
Kosovo province, but called on Yugoslavia to grant a high degree
of autonomy to ethnic Albanians in the province.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who is on a brief visit to Albania, talked with
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano and Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo on the Kosovo issue and German-Albanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has a 90 percent ethnic Albanian majority which is
attempting to seek independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said the situation in the province is drawing the
attention of the international community, especially from Germany
which is facing a consistent influx of Kosovo Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Between 500 and 2,000 Kosovo Albanian refugees have been
arriving in Germany every month, while 140,000 have already
requested political asylum, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
As to relations with Albania, Kinkel said Germany is concerned
about political and economic ties with Albania.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said Germany hopes the Balkan region and Albania will
become stable, adding that his country is hopeful that Albania
will play a stable role in the Balkan area.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel appealed to all the parties in Albania to adopt a
peaceful and cooperative attitude. He urged the opposition
Democratic Party to return to the parliament and participate in
constitutional drafting.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister said the international community is
willing to assist Albania, but warned that if Albania fails to
achieve national reconciliation, the country may receive only a
small amount of international aid.
</P>
<P>
In talks with Kinkel, Nano said the Albanian government regards
Germany as one of its most important European partners and asked
Germany to bring Albania into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Paskal Milo, Albanian foreign minister, also said Albania will
increase cooperation with Germany and bring bilateral ties to "an
unprecedented level." 
</P>
</TEXT>
