<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nagano Olympic Winter Games Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 7 (Xinhua) -- With ringing of the Zenkoji
Temple bell and the entrance of 234kg sumo wrestler at the Opening
Ceremony, the curtain of the 18th Olympic Winter Games raised here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Emperor Akihito declared open of the games, which will last 16 days
till February 22.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and International Olympic
Committee president (IOC) Juan Antonio Samaranch attended the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,339 skiers, skaters and sledders from 72 countries and
regions have registered their participation in the games, which
features 68 events from 14 sports. All of those made the games the
biggest ever in Winter Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland and Britain deserved a special mention. The two have
been the only countries taking part in all summer and winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Five countries of Azerbaijan, Kenya, Macedonia, Uruguay and
Venezuela made their first appearance in winter Olympics and three new
sports of snowboarding, curling and women's ice hockey were added in
the official programme.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied with the job the organizers have done for the
games," said Samaranch on Friday.
</P>
<P>
China has sent 61 skiers and skaters for the games, taking part in
the sports of speed skating, short-track speed skating, figure
skating, women's ice hockey, women's biathlon, free style skiing and
cross country skiing.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that Japan hosts the Winter Olympics. In the
year 1972, Sapporo hosted the 11th edition.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony tried to bring the East and West together,
from Kagaribi bonfires at the four corners of the center stage, to the
choirs of Beethoven from five continents.
</P>
<P>
After the bell ringing in the ancient Zenkoji Temple, Japan's sumo
hero Akebono took the stage with other contenders of the sport.
Akebono performed the ring-entering ceremony dohyo-iri, raised each
leg in turn and stamped on the ground to drive out evil spirits from
the stadium before the entry of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
Akebono, as a yokozuna, or Grand Champion, won much respect in
Japan for his outstanding achievement in the Japanese ancient sport.
</P>
<P>
After that, the Olympic flame entered into the spotlight and it was
passed to professional figure skater Midori Ito, who used it to ignite
the Olympic Cauldron.
</P>
<P>
The message of peace was emphasized when the torch was carried by
Chris Moon into the stadium. Moon, a former British military officer
who lost his right arm and part of his leg while deactivating a land
mine in Africa, now is campaigning for a ban on antipersonnel land
mines.
</P>
<P>
Ito has been the only Japanese figure skater who won a medal in
winter Olympics. In the Albertville games in 1992, Ito claimed the
silver medal in the women's singles event. With the silver, she
became a superstar in her native land after returning to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The flame was kindled in the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece in
December last year and it was carried in the torch relay through all
of Japan's 47 prefectures on three routes before arriving in Nagano
city Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In the finale of the ceremony, singers on five continents -- in
Berlin, Sydney, New York, Beijing, Cape Point of South Africa -- gave
a simultaneous Global Grand Chorus of "Ode to Joy" from Beethoven's
No.9 "Choral" under the baton of maestro Seiji Ozawa.
</P>
<P>
During the performance of the "Ode to Joy", 81 ballet dancers
ignited four kagaribi bonfires around the center stage while
performing a ballet symbolizing the Winter Olympics sporting events.
</P>
<P>
Men's hockey tournament with Italy taking on Kazakstan, Austria
playing Slovakia, Germany meeting Japan and France against Belarus are
scheduled later in the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0170 </DOCNO>
