<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Program to Preserve Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A five-year program has been
launched by the Forestry and Environment Ministry for the
conservation, management and development of forests in Sri Lanka,
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the program covers areas such as forest land
allocation, multiple use of natural forests, forests conservation
and management, agro forestry extension, commercial plantation
development and the development of forests-based industries.
</P>
<P>
It will also help the locals boost the development of home
gardens.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 1.88 billion rupees (30.3 million
U.S. dollars) for the program, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
During the past decades, Sri Lanka's forest cover has decreased
significantly. According to estimates by local forestry experts,
some 44,000 hectares of forest will diminish each year in the
country because of shifting cultivation, timber exploitation and
fuel wood collection. 
</P>
