<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Plantation Workers Continue Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 7 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide strike by Sri
Lanka's plantation workers entered its third day Saturday after
their talks with the employers' association over a wage hike
reached a deadlock Friday.
</P>
<P>
Major trade unions, including the Ceylon Workers Congress
(CWC), did not attend a meeting convened by Labor Minister John
Seneviratne Friday afternoon, and a separate meeting between
plantation companies and the CWC in the evening also failed to
bring about a settlement.
</P>
<P>
The unions did not go to the meeting on the ground that the
employers must hold direct talks with them.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the trade unions said Saturday that they
would continue the strike until their demands were met.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 workers in tea and rubber estates staged a strike
Thursday after a breakdown in talks with their employers over the
wage hike.
</P>
<P>
The unions demanded having their daily salary raised from 83
rupees (1.34 U.S. dollars) at present to 105 rupees (1.69 dollars)
while their companies only agreed to pay 93 rupees (1.5 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tuesday, Seneviratne intervened and urged the companies to
offer 100 rupees (1.61 dollars) as a compromise.
</P>
<P>
The last strike by estate workers in April 1996, which lasted
for one week, was estimated to have cost the government 500
million rupees (8.1 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
