<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- At least 198 local residents
were wounded by firecrackers during the Chinese lunar New Year
celebrations, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Eight people including an 8-year-old kid have their eyeballs
removed by hospitals, Beijing Daily said.
</P>
<P>
The firecrackers also caused 26 fires throughout the city
during the week-long celebrations starting from January 27, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has banned the shooting-off of
firecrackers in the city since 1993 as an effort to protect the
environment and people's life.
</P>
<P>
But the beginning of the Year of the Tiger has seen more
violations of the ban than the beginning of the Year of Ox (last
year).
</P>
<P>
About 350 persons have been penalized, including 17 being
detained, for violating the rule during the New Year holidays, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has warned local residents to stay
away from firecrackers during the up-coming Lantern Festival which
falls on February 11, it said. 
