<HEADLINE> Travelling Safe, Timely During Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Travelling during the 1998
Spring Festival was safe and timely despite the bad weather
affection, thanks to concerted efforts in the transportation
sectors.
</P>
<P>
"In the face of menacing weather, transportation authorities
have made every effort to resolve any traffic bottleneck, and are
stressing safety," Yan Hui, an official from the State Economic
and Trade Commission, was quoted by today's China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
This year's Spring Festival fell on January 28. The Jan. 8-Feb.
28 period was announced as the travel period for many people who
travel during this period for festive gatherings or family reunion.
</P>
<P>
"Nationwide, the railway sector handled 77.3 million passengers
during the Jan 8-29 period, up 3.6 percent over the same period of
1997," Wang Yaru, a Ministry of Railways official, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
About 710 million travelers journeyed by bus during Jan 8-27,
three percent more compared with the same period of last year,
according to the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
A total of 41,653 flights in 45 cities across the country
transported nearly 4.35 million passengers. No air accidents
occurred.
</P>
<P>
A heavy snowfall hitting central China's Hunan province on
January 22 cut power supply for a major section of the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railway line, an arterial line linking the north
with the south. Tens of millions of passengers were held up in
Guangzhou City.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways sent 20 additional trains to help
these stranded passengers. About 220,000 passengers left Guangzhou
by train in the daytime, 140,000 by bus, and 30,000 by air.
</P>
<P>
Officials from transportation sectors promised to strengthen
safety inspection and prevention work. They hoped to closely
cooperate with meteorological bureaux to ensure Spring Festival
travel goes well in the rest period of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
