<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Improves Weather-Warning System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is equipping its
meteorological networks with modern technology for precise weather
forecasting and warning against natural calamities, the Associated
Press of Bangladesh (APB) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under an 825-million-taka (17.9 million U.S. dollars) project,
which is being implemented, a new radar will be installed in
Bangpur, 260 kilometers northwest of Dhaka, first ever in North
Bengal, to gather data from all over the region, Indian
river-catchment areas and Ganges basin, APB said.
</P>
<P>
The existing radar at the Met Office headquarters in Dhaka will
be replaced with a new one which will provide precise forecast on
rain, flood and other natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
A microwave link between the Hangpura TV and the Storm Warning
Center (SWC) at the Met Office in Dhaka will be established to
telecast updated weather forecast directly.
</P>
<P>
The Flood Forecasting Center of the Water Development Board in
the capital city will also be linked with the SWC at the Met
Office headquarters to instantaneously supply flood-related data
to the center.
</P>
<P>
Microwave from the SWC will also link up with the Prime
Minister's Office to keep the prime minister posted about latest
weather situation as well as severe natural calamities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
