<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico, US Agree On War Against Drugs Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and the United
States have agreed on a bilateral strategy against drug
trafficking based on mutual respect for sovereignty and
territorial jurisdiction, the Mexican government announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green said the strategy was
agreed on after nine months of talks between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
She said the strategy establishes respect for existing national
programs, sovereignty, territorial jurisdiction and the principles
of reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
Under the strategy, the two countries will seek more
cooperation in the war against money laundering and trafficking of
arms, reduce the cultivation and demand for drugs and allow air,
sea and land interception.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the two countries signed a 41-page memorandum of
cooperation in Washington on the war against drugs, said the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Green met U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
U.S. government Anti-Drug Director Barry McCaffrey and Attorney
General Janet Reno to discuss anti-drug cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two nations started negotiations in May 1997, when U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
signed a document to establish an anti-drug bi-national alliance.
</P>
<P>
Green said that cooperation on the war against drugs does not
mean subordination.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important for us to understand that cooperation
does not imply subordination in any way. We are cooperating with
the United States on an equal basis that is mutually beneficial,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation will be increased to combat and eliminate the
potential of official corruption in drug trafficking on the
borders between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two governments will strengthen their cooperation on the
exchange of information and training. They will also apply, in the
most effective manner, the existing laws and regulations to detect
and punish money laundering in both countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
