<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Set Up 5,000 Biogas Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will set up 5,000
biogas plants across the country in a bid to speed up the
implementation of the biogas pilot project, local press reports
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under a 68.9-million-taka (1.49 million U.S. dollars) project
which has been taken by the government, 5,000 biogas plants based
on cow dung are expected to be set up at the union level by the
end of the current fiscal year (from July 1, 1997 to June 30,
1998).
</P>
<P>
The plants, costing 15,000-18,000 taka (326-391 dollars), are
being installed in the rural areas with the technical assistance
of the Institute of Fuel Research and Development.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide 5,000 taka (108.6 dollars) for each
plant as subsidy, and the rest could be obtained as soft loans
from the nationalized commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,128 personnel having science background will be
imparted training in biogas technology, and three such training
courses have already been completed.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of the project, the country's fuel
crisis is likely to ease to a great extent and adequate
production of bio-manure and preservation of bio-cycle will be
ensured, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
