<HEADLINE> Kenyan Makes Debut in Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan runners have always
been medal favourites on tracks, could they run over their rivals on
snow and ice?
</P>
<P>
They hardly have any chance this time, but who knows in the future.
The African country has started to try winter sports when Philip Boit
became the only Kenyan athlete at the 18th Olympic Winter Games which
opens here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Blinking in the glare of photographers' flashes and television
lights, Kenya's first-ever Olympic skier is jostled for comment at
every appearance. Once a policeman and middle-distance runners,
26-year-old Philip is Kenya's first, and only, Winter Games qualifier.
</P>
<P>
With him is Henry Bitok, 29, previously a navy guard and
world-class steeplechaser who failed to qualify, but is in Nagano as a
reserve.
</P>
<P>
The pair, who had never seen snow in their lives before, abandoned
their former lives two years ago when they went to Finland to train as
cross-country skiers.
</P>
<P>
Now they spend at least seven months of the year training and
competing in Finland.
</P>
<P>
"They are both very good athletes in Kenya, although they're
perhaps not good enough for the Olympics. But they are open minded and
they wanted to see if a good athlete in one sport can be trained to
perform really well in another," said Mats Olsson of the Kenyan
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Boit will compete in the 10km classic race on Feburuary 12 and in
the 15km free style pursuit on St. Valentine's Day -- February 14.
</P>
<P>
So how does his coach fancy his protege's chances?
</P>
<P>
"We have to be realistic. If philip has a good race he will come in
nine or ten minutes after the winner. I'm hoping he will do the best
he can do. That's enough for me," Jussi Lehtinen said.
</P>
<P>
Philip was more proud to compete in winter Olympics. "I am proud to
be here and I hope that next time we'll be in bigger group," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
