<HEADLINE> Prodi Sees Violation of Law in Cable Car Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi said Friday that he sees violation of law in a fatal cable
car accident involving a U.S. military jet on Tuesday, in which 20
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister said that his government is not
questioning Italy's membership of NATO or friendship with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Twenty people were killed when a U.S. Marine EA-6B electronic
warfare plane sliced a cable line with its tail fin in northern
Italy Tuesday, sending a cable car and the 20 people aboard
plunging to their death.
</P>
<P>
The accident has sparked anti-Americanism and anti-military
sentiment in Italy.
</P>
<P>
"We are in complete agreement that the plane was flying below
the approved altitude," Prodi said in remarks released by the ANSA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
"What has to be discussed is why," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi also said his government wants necessary training
activities in Italy by military forces of whatever nationality to
be such as to avoid "placing the population's safety at risk in
any way."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the government requires laws
governing military activities on Italian territory to be respected
and applied "in the firmest and most rigorous way."
</P>
<P>
"This disaster was provoked by an indisputable violation of the
law," he said, "no regulation or training need can permit flying
low enought to cut the cables of a cableway."
</P>
<P>
Prodi also called for investigations into the disaster to be
completed "with a maximum of speed and with full transparency."
</P>
<P>
Citing a statement from the U.S. ambassador to Italy Thamas
Foglietta, Prodi said that this was what President Bill Clinton
promised in a telephone conversation shortly after the disaster,
"and this is what will be done."
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the cable car accident, Italy's leftist party
members have demanded the closing of U.S. bases in Italy and an
Italian exit from NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
