<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rescue Operations Continue in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 7 (Xinhua) -- Rescue operations resumed
Saturday after a dozen bags of human bodies were found in the
previous days at the crash site of an ill-fate Cebu Pacific
aircraft at Mt. Sumagaya in Mindanao, southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The bodies were so badly mutilated it was impossible to tell
how many of the 99 passengers and five crew members aboard the
doomed plane have been found since search and rescue operations
started Monday, rescuers said.
</P>
<P>
Many of the bodies are in a deep ravine inaccessible to
helicopters, the rescuers said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said around 20 bags of human bodies, or at
least 46 dismembered bodies, had been retrieved by rescuers as by
Friday noon time at the crash site on Mt. Sumagaya on the southern
island of Mindanao. But so far there has been no official report
on the number of recovered bodies.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams Friday called for "more muscular men and shovels"
to help dig up an area of the crash site that they believe could
hold a big part of the fuselage of the plane that crashed into the
mountain on its way from Manila to Cagayan de Oro, Mindanao,
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds, fog and rain have grounded helicopters and
hampered rescue efforts for much of the last five days. About 100
volunteer rescuers, weak from lack of food, began leaving the
crash site Friday after helicopters were unable to deliver them
water and provisions for more than a day.
</P>
<P>
At the foot of the mountain, anxious relatives of victims
shouted at officials, asking why food was not being taken to the
rescuers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, five British forensic experts arrived in Cagayan de
Oro Friday to help identify the bodies retrieved from the crash
site.
</P>
<P>
There is still no word from rescuers combing the crash site on
any survivors of the 104 people aboard the ill-fated Cebu Pacific
Flight 387.
</P>
<P>
Rescue officials said earlier that it was a "remote
possibility" that anyone could survive the air disaster, the worst
ever in Philippine history.
</P>
<P>
Government doctors who were sent to villages near the crash
site echoed the sentiment, saying that if there were any
survivors, they would have already died.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams reached the impact point of the plane Friday
afternoon and found the wings, tail and two engines of the doomed
jetliner. But the "black box," the flight data recorder that will
pinpoint the cause of the accident, has not been recovered.
</P>
<P>
Rescue officials said it would take at least two months to
clear the crash site, an area of one square kilometer, and another
six months to undergo the painful procedure of identifying the
remains of crash victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
