<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Rejects Use of Force Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, February 6 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Fernando Naranjo Friday expressed his country's objections to a
U.S. ordered military attack against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica hopes the Iraq-U.S. crisis can be resolved
through diplomacy and supports diplomatic actions by
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, Naranjo told the press.
</P>
<P>
Naranjo met U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Bill
Richardson Friday, who arrived here on a tour of nine African and
Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the United States would endorse an attack
against Iraq if Baghdad prevents U.N. experts from inspecting
places, including presidential palaces, suspected of warehousing
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"Our country does not believe in military solutions. The last
thing we would want is an action of that kind," stressed Naranjo.
"The U.N. secretary general must go to Baghdad," he added.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is a non-permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council, representing Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Annan's visit to Baghdad may be made this weekend, but it has
not been decided, said Naranjo.
</P>
<P>
Several nations, including Russia, France and China, opposed
the use of force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. diplomat said that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein must
cease his hostility and aggression toward neighboring countries
and must comply with the U.N. resolutions agreed upon at the end
of the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
