<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Fails to Meet EMU Inflation Criteria in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 6 (Xinhua) -- All European Union (EU) member
states but Greece met the inflation criteria for economic and
monetary union in 1997, it was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
Greece, with a 5.4 percent inflation rate, is the only EU
member which had an average annual inflation rate exceeding the
top permissible rate, according to Eurostat, the EU's statistical
office based in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The top permissable rate is determined by calculating the
average rate of the three best performing countries plus 1.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
EU Economic Affairs Commissioner Yves Thibault de Silguy early
this week defined the inflation rate to be used in the European
Commission's convergence report on March 25.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU executive would take an arithmetic average of
the three lowest rates in the EU, based on 12 months' figures, to
determine the top permissible rate -- the average plus a 1.5
percentage point margin allowed in the Maastricht treaty.
</P>
<P>
The three lowest rates, according to Eurostat data, were
Ireland #,Austria and Finland all with 1.2 percent, thus making
the top permissible rate 2.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
