<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Astronomers Find Gamma-ray Bursts Coming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 6 (Xinhua) -- British astronomers have found
evidence that gamma-ray bursts detected in space are coming from
the most distant known objects in the universe.
</P>
<P>
The dimmest burst now observed may have been given off when the
universe was only one twentieth of its present age, the Royal
Astronomical Society(RAS) said Friday in a press notice.
</P>
<P>
According to a team headed by Dr Ralph Wijers at the University
of Cambridge's Institute of Astronomy, it has taken about 15
billion years, almost the whole time the universe has existed, for
these bursts to reach the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers reached their conclusions by comparing the observed
strengths of large numbers of gamma-ray bursts with predictions
based on the theory that the bursts are linked to the death-throes
of massive stars, the RAS said.
</P>
<P>
Gamma-ray bursts are flashes of gamma rays lasting on average
10 seconds. They were first noticed in the 1960s but until
recently astronomers did not know exactly where they are coming
from.
</P>
<P>
The energy released by a gamma-ray burst is phenomenal, usually
greater than all the energy produced by the Sun in its
10-billion-year life.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers suggest that it is something similar to the
collapse of a massive star that causes the stupendous bursts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980207.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills More People in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 18 other people
have died of cholera in central and southern Mozambique in the
last few days, the Ministry of Health announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure brings to 318 the number of people who have
fallen victim to the highly-infectious disease since it broke out
in the country in August, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Ministry of Health, Avertino Barreto, said
21 people died in Mozambique's second city, Beira, at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said 732 cases of the disease have been diagnosed since the
epidemic broke out 10 days ago in Beira, the capital of Sofala
Province. He describes the situation as serious.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has diagnosed 12,132 cases of cholera since the
first case was reported on the 13th of August.
</P>
<P>
Cholera is an acute infection of the small intestines, causing
severe diarrhoea and vomiting. The disease is associated with
poor sanitary conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
